agers}}\n{{AEK Athens F.C. managers}}\n{{Atromitos F.C. managers}}\n{{PAOK F.C. managers}}\n{{APOEL FC managers}}\n{{Al-Hilal FC managers}}\n{{Al-Sharjah SCC managers}}\n{{Panathinaikos F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donis, Giorgos}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Frankfurt]]\n[[Category:Greece international footballers]]\n[[Category:Greek football managers]]\n[[Category:German footballers]]\n[[Category:German people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panathinaikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:AE Larissa FC managers]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:PAOK FC managers]]\n[[Category:APOEL FC managers]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Al Hilal SFC managers]]\n[[Category:Al-Sharjah SCC managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Hesse]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games gold medalists for Greece]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean Games medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1991 Mediterranean Games]]\n[[Category:Saudi Professional League managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek football manager and former player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Giorgos Donis\n| image =\n| fullname = Georgios Donis\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1969|10|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Frankfurt]], [[West Germany]]\n| death_date  =\n| height = {{height|m=1.80}}\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] (manager)\n| youthyears1 = 1986\u20131987 | youthclubs1 = AO Pavlos Melas\n| youthyears2 = 1987\u20131988 | youthclubs2 = [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]\n| youthyears3 = 1988\u20131989 | youthclubs3 = [[Athinaikos F.C.|Athinaikos]]\n| youthyears4 = 1989\u20131990 | youthclubs4 = [[Panargiakos F.C.|Panargiakos]]\n| years1 = 1990\u20131991 | clubs1 = [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]] | caps1 = 22 | goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 1991\u20131996 | clubs2 = [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] | caps2 = 107 | goals2 = 31\n| years3 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs3 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] | caps3 = 22 | goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 1997\u20131998 | clubs4 = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]] | caps4 = 30 | goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 1999      | clubs5 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] | caps5 = 7 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 1999\u20132000 | clubs6 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] | caps6 = 21 | goals6 = 0\n| totalcaps = 239 | totalgoals = 43\n| nationalyears1= 1991\u20131997 | nationalteam1= [[Greece national football team|Greece]]\n| nationalcaps1= 24 | nationalgoals1 = 5\n| manageryears1 = 2002\u20132004 | managerclubs1 = [[Ilisiakos F.C.|Ilisiakos]]\n| manageryears2 = 2004\u20132008 | managerclubs2 = [[AEL 1964 FC|AEL]]\n| manageryears3 = 2008\u20132009 | managerclubs3 = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| manageryears4 = 2009\u20132012 | managerclubs4 = [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]]\n| manageryears5 = 2012\u20132013 | managerclubs5 = [[PAOK FC|PAOK]]\n| manageryears6 = 2013\u20132015 | managerclubs6 = [[APOEL FC|APOEL]]\n| manageryears7 = 2015\u20132016 | managerclubs7 = [[Al-Hilal FC|Al-Hilal]]\n| manageryears8 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs8 = [[Al-Sharjah SCC|Al-Sharjah]]\n| manageryears9 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs9 = [[APOEL FC|APOEL]]\n| manageryears10 = 2018\u2013    | managerclubs10 = [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]}}\n\n'''Giorgos Donis''' ({{lang-el|\u0393\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2}}, born 22 October 1969) is a Greek former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]]. He is the current manager of [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]. He was the first ever Greek to play in the [[English Premier League]]. In England, he was also known as '''George Donis'''.\n\n==Early years==\nDonis was born and raised in [[Frankfurt]], [[West Germany]] until he was six years old and the family moved back to their native [[Greece]]. His parents had lived in Frankfurt for \"many years\" and he has still family ties there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.org/news/newsid=2034035.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430095524/http://www.uefa.org/news/newsid%3D2034035.html|archive-date=30 April 2016|title=Donis back where it all began with APOEL|date=2013-12-09|publisher=uefa.org|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nGiorgos Donis started his senior career with [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]] in 1990, and after one successful year he moved to [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The fans of Panathinaikos, known for their love for nicknames, named him ''the Train'' for his remarkable acceleration.\n\nOn 5 June 1996, after helping the Greek club reach the [[UEFA Champions League]] semi-finals against [[Ajax FC]], Donis moved to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on a free transfer, making use of the then recent [[Bosman ruling]] signing for 1.1 billion drachmas, a record amount for Greek players at the time. He had an erratic season with Blackburn, scoring against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and Coventry City.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/donis-fills-the-void-in-attack-1364578.html|title=Donis fills the void in attack\n|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=21 September 1996 |accessdate=6 November 2009| location=London| first=Steve| last=Edwards}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4thegame.com/matchcentre/premiership/reports/75305/brfcccfc.html |title=Blackburn 4 \u2013 0 Coventry |publisher=4TheGame |date=11 January 1997 |accessdate=6 November 2009 }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nHe then headed back home to play for [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]], before moving back to England again, playing for [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] where he ended his career.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-dejected-ipswich-head-for-playoff-lottery-1092655.html|title=Dejected Ipswich head for play-off lottery|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=9 May 1999 |accessdate=6 November 2009| location=London| first=Kieran| last=Daley}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nHe made his debut for the [[Greece national football team|Greek national football team]] on 22 December 1991, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Malta national football team|Malta]] for the [[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying]] round.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1992/matches/round=218/match=3021/index.html UEFA EURO 1992 - History - Malta-Greece]</ref> He appeared in 24 matches and scored five goals during his international career with Grecce.\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===AEL===\nAfter the end of his playing career, he turned to coaching. Starting in 2002, he led [[Zografou]]-based [[Ilisiakos F.C.|Ilisiakos]] in two consecutive promotions from 4th to 2nd Greek football level. He then made the move to [[AEL 1964 FC|AEL]], where after one season he managed to bring the team to the [[Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]] from the second division and finished them in 8th place the following year. In 2007, Larissa finished only 10th in the league but he managed to bring them the [[2006\u201307 Greek Cup|Greek Cup]] after defeating [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] 2\u20131 in the final.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=535707.html Unlikely Larissa take Greek Cup]</ref> In his first taste of European football management, his team AE Larissa defeated his former team [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] to reach the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Cup]] [[2007\u201308 UEFA Cup group stage|group stages]].<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/news/kind=1/newsid=599067.html Larissa explain it all]</ref> He finished a great year in 6th place in the league, missing out on the season play-off's on goal difference.\n\n===AEK Athens===\nOn 25 April 2008, Donis stepped down as manager of AEL and on 14 May he was appointed as head coach of [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]].<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=696219.html Donis handed AEK post]</ref>\nOn 17 November 2008, due to a string of poor performances and early knock out from the [[UEFA Cup]], AEK parted company with him just six months after his appointment.<ref>[http://www.sportingreece.com/kb/article.asp?fIndex=2557 Donis's brief tenure at AEK is over] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217162426/http://www.sportingreece.com/kb/article.asp?fIndex=2557 |date=17 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Atromitos===\nIn 2009, Donis was appointed by [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]] and in the 2010\u201311 season he again reached the [[2010\u201311 Greek Cup|Greek Cup]] [[2011 Greek Cup Final|Final]] only to lose 0\u20133 to his former team [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]. In the next year, Atromitos enjoyed another successful spell under his guidance, reaching the [[2011\u201312 Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] [[2012 Greek Cup Final|Final]] for a second consecutive time (losing 1\u20132 to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] at [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]]), as well as participating at the [[2011\u201312 Superleague Greece#Playoffs|Greek Superleauge play-offs]].\n\n===PAOK===\nOn 31 May 2012, [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] appointed Donis as the new manager of the club, on a two-year contract, with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paokfc.gr/swift.jsp?CMCCode=1002&CMRCode=16UHQPGGE |script-title=el:\u039d\u03ad\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03bd\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf \u0393\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 |publisher=paokfc.gr |language=Greek |date=31 May 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012052011/http://www.paokfc.gr/swift.jsp?CMCCode=1002&CMRCode=16UHQPGGE |archivedate=12 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> On 28 April 2013, after a crucial defeat 0\u20132 and the elimination in the semi-final of [[2012\u201313 Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]] by [[Asteras Tripoli F.C.|Asteras Tripolis]], he was sacked by chairman [[Ivan Savvidis]].<ref>[http://olapaok.gr/podosfairo/Proponitis/lunetai_to_symvolaio_me_dwnh_paizei_kai_toy_ivan.2232020.html \u039b\u03cd\u03bd\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c5\u03bc\u03b2\u03cc\u03bb\u03b1\u03b9\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7, \u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0399\u03b2\u03ac\u03bd] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501061512/http://olapaok.gr/podosfairo/Proponitis/lunetai_to_symvolaio_me_dwnh_paizei_kai_toy_ivan.2232020.html |date=1 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===APOEL===\nOn 11 October 2013, Donis signed a contract until the end of the 2013\u201314 season with the reigning [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] champions [[APOEL FC|APOEL]], replacing [[Paulo S\u00e9rgio Bento Brito|Paulo S\u00e9rgio]] who had been fired on 4 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=10284&tt=graphic&lang=l1 |publisher=APOEL FC |script-title=el:\u03a5\u03c0\u03ad\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c8\u03b5 \u03bf \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 |date=11 October 2013 |accessdate=11 October 2013 |language=Greek |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012032209/http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=10284&tt=graphic&lang=l1 |archivedate=12 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> In his first season at APOEL, Donis achieved to win the [[Double (association football)|double]]. He won his first title with APOEL on 21 May 2014, when he led his team to a 2\u20130 victory over [[Ermis Aradippou]] in the [[2013\u201314 Cypriot Cup|Cypriot Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=11366&tt=graphic&lang=l1 |script-title=el:\u0395\u03a1\u039c\u0397\u03a3 \u0391\u03a1\u0391\u0394\u0399\u03a0\u03a0\u039f\u03a5 0-2 \u0391\u03a0\u039f\u0395\u039b |language=Greek |publisher=APOEL FC |date=21 May 2014 |accessdate=21 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524135627/http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=11366&tt=graphic&lang=l1 |archivedate=24 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/05/21/cyprus/cup/apoel-nicosia/ermis-fc-aradippou/1668957/|title=APOEL vs. Ermis 2-0|trans-title=|publisher=Soccerway|date=21 May 2014|accessdate=21 May 2014}}</ref> Ten days later, Donis won also the [[2013\u201314 Cypriot First Division|Cypriot First Division]] after APOEL's 1\u20130 away victory against [[AEL Limassol]] in the title deciding match and won his first league title in his managerial career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=cyp/news/newsid=2102109.html|title=Sheridan strike hands APOEL Cypriot title|publisher=UEFA|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2014/05/31/cyprus/1-division/ael-limassol/apoel-nicosia/1662145/|title=AEL vs. APOEL 0-1|publisher=Soccerway|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a successful first season in the club, Giorgos Donis signed a one-year contract extension with APOEL on 26 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sport-fm.com.cy/podosfairo/apoel/item/7330-\u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb-\u03ad\u03b2\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5-\u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae-\u03bf-\u03b3\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2-\u03b4\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2.html |title=\u0388\u03b2\u03b1\u03bb\u03b5 \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03bf \u0393\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 |publisher=sport-fm.com.cy |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=26 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629173328/http://www.sport-fm.com.cy/podosfairo/apoel/item/7330-%CE%B1%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%B5%CE%BB-%CE%AD%CE%B2%CE%B1%CE%BB%CE%B5-%CF%85%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%B3%CF%81%CE%B1%CF%86%CE%AE-%CE%BF-%CE%B3%CE%B9%CF%8E%CF%81%CE%B3%CE%BF%CF%82-%CE%B4%CF%8E%CE%BD%CE%B7%CF%82.html |archivedate=29 June 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref> In August 2014, Donis led APOEL into the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stages]] of the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League]], after eliminating [[Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi|HJK Helsinki]] (4\u20132 on aggregate) in the third qualifying round and trashing [[AaB Fodbold|Aalborg BK]] 5\u20131 on aggregate in the play-off round of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000547/match=2014209/postmatch/report/index.html|title=APOEL ease past AaB and into group stage|trans-title=|publisher=UEFA|date=26 August 2014|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> APOEL were drawn in Group F alongside [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] and [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2137672.html|title=Holders Real Madrid draw Liverpool in group stage|trans-title=|publisher=UEFA|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> Donis led his team to some great performances in the group stage, but APOEL managed to collect only one point after drawing 1\u20131 with Ajax at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000548/match=2014390/postmatch/lineups/index.html|title=Ajax thrash APOEL to finish third in Group F|trans-title=|publisher=UEFA|date=10 December 2014|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> In their other five Group F matches, APOEL lost twice to Barcelona (0\u20134 at home, 0\u20131 away), lost twice to Paris Saint-Germain (0\u20131 at home, 0\u20131 away) and also lost to Ajax 0\u20134 away.\n\nOn 6 January 2015, APOEL and Giorgos Donis parted company by mutual agreement after a poor run of performances and results, culminating in a 1\u20131 home draw against the last-placed [[Ayia Napa F.C.|Ayia Napa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=12482&tt=graphic&lang=l1 |title=\u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ad\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03bb\u03cd\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5 \u0393\u03b9\u03ce\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7 |publisher=APOEL FC |date=6 January 2015 |accessdate=6 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226152443/http://www.apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=12482&tt=graphic&lang=l1 |archivedate=26 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===Al-Hilal===\nOn 25 February 2015, he was appointed as the new manager of [[Al-Hilal FC|Al-Hilal]] in Saudi Arabia, signing a contract until the end of the season. He helped Al-Hilal to qualify in the semi-final of the [[2015 AFC Champions League]]. On 6 June, Donis won the first title with Al-Hilal after defeating [[Al Nassr FC|Al-Nassr]] in the final of the [[2015 King Cup of Champions]].\n\n===Al-Sharjah===\nOn 28 July 2016, he was appointed as the new manager of [[Al-Sharjah SCC|Al-Sharjah]] in UAE, signing a contract until the summer of 2018.\n\n===Second spell in APOEL===\nOn 28 July 2017, Donis signed a contract until the end of the 2017-18 season with the reigning [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] champions [[APOEL FC|APOEL]], replacing [[Mario Been]] who had been sacked by APOEL following a 1-0 away European defeat to [[FC Viitorul Constanta|Viitorul Constanta]].<ref>[https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/bliksemontslag-been-bij-apoel-nicosia Bliksemontslag Been bij APOEL Nicosia] - Voetbal International {{in lang|nl}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sport24.gr/football/Cyprus/o-dwnhs-th-stigmh-twn-ypografwn-ston-apoel.4784397.html \u039f \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03b3\u03bc\u03ae \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ce\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0391\u03a0\u039f\u0395\u039b]</ref> On 23 March 2018, APOEL have sacked Donis, and have replaced him with 40-year-old Portuguese manager [[Bruno Baltazar]]. The last straw seemed to be APOEL\u2019s recent 4-2 away defeat against [[Apollon Limassol]], which saw APOEL fall out of first place in the Cypriot First Division. Expectations have become quite high at APOEL in recent years. The Nicosia giants have won the [[Cypriot First Division]] the last 5 seasons, and 7 of the last 9 campaigns. With that domestic run now in jeopardy, APOEL have made the move to replace Donis with the Portuguese coach.<ref>[http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/podosfairo/teleiwnei-apo-ton-apoel-o-dwnis/3508337 \u03a4\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03ce\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0391\u03a0\u039f\u0395\u039b \u03bf \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2]</ref><ref>[https://alphanews.live/sports/parelthon-kai-episema-o-dones-apo-ton-apoel \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b5\u03bb\u03b8\u03cc\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b5\u03c0\u03af\u03c3\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 \u03bf \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0391\u03a0\u039f\u0395\u039b]</ref>\n\n===Panathinaikos===\nDonis was appointed on 3 July 2018 as the new manager of his former club as a player, [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]], signing a three-year contract.<ref>[https://www.sdna.gr/podosfairo/superleague/article/485360/episimo-donis-trietias-ston-panathinaiko \u0394\u03ce\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03b5\u03c4\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc]</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 1 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"115\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"30\"|Nation\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"120\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\" width=\"120\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\" width=\"120\"|Record\n|-\n!G\n!W\n!D\n!L\n!Win %\n|-\n|align=center|[[Ilisiakos F.C.|Ilisiakos]]\n|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 July 2002\n|align=center|30 June 2004\n{{WDL|47|29|11|7|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[AEL 1964 FC|AEL]]\n|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 July 2004\n|align=center|24 April 2008\n{{WDL|110|39|32|39|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[A.E.K. Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|14 May 2008\n|align=center|15 November 2008\n{{WDL|10|3|6|1|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]]\n|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 July 2009\n|align=center|30 May 2012\n{{WDL|111|41|37|33|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[PAOK FC|PAOK]]\n|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|align=center|1 June 2012\n|align=center|29 April 2013\n{{WDL|42|26|9|7|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[APOEL FC|APOEL]]\n|{{flagicon|CYP}}\n|align=center|11 October 2013\n|align=center|6 January 2015\n{{WDL|61|35|14|12|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=center|[[Al-Hilal FC|Al-Hilal]]\n|{{flagicon|KSA}}\n|align=center|4 March 2015\n|align=center|18 May 2016\n{{WDL|66|45|11|10|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|[[Al-Sharjah SCC|Al-Sharjah]]\n|{{flagicon|UAE}}\n|28 July 2016\n|1 January 2017\n{{WDL|13|4|2|7|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|[[APOEL FC|APOEL]]\n|{{flagicon|CYP}}\n|28 July 2017\n|23 March 2018\n{{WDL|41|25|8|8|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|[[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]\n|{{flagicon|GRE}}\n|3 July 2018\n|''Present''\n{{WDL|67|30|17|20|decimals=1}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Total\n{{WDLtot|568|277|147|144|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n\n;'''[[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]]'''\n*[[Superleague Greece|Greek League]]: [[1994\u201395 Alpha Ethniki|1994\u201395]], [[1995\u201396 Alpha Ethniki|1995\u201396]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[1992\u201393 Greek Cup|1992\u201393]], [[1993\u201394 Greek Cup|1993\u201394]], [[1994\u201395 Greek Cup|1994\u201395]]\n*[[Greek Super Cup]]: 1993, 1994\n\n===Manager===\n\n;'''[[AEL 1964 FC|AEL]]'''\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2006\u201307 Greek Cup|2006\u201307]]\n*[[Football League (Greece)|Greek Second Division]]: 2004\u201305\n\n;'''[[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]]'''\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: Runner-up [[2010\u201311 Greek Cup|2010\u201311]], [[2011\u201312 Greek Cup|2011\u201312]]\n\n;'''[[Ilisiakos F.C.|Ilisiakos]]'''\n*[[Gamma Ethniki]]: 2003\u201304\n*[[Delta Ethniki]]: 2002\u201303\n\n;'''[[APOEL FC|APOEL]]'''\n*[[Cypriot First Division|Cypriot League]]: [[2013\u201314 Cypriot First Division|2013\u201314]], [[2017\u201318 Cypriot First Division|2017\u201318]]\n*[[Cypriot Cup]]: [[2013\u201314 Cypriot Cup|2013\u201314]]\n\n;'''[[Al-Hilal FC|Al-Hilal]]'''\n*[[King Cup of Champions]]: [[2015 King Cup of Champions|2015]]\n*[[Saudi Super Cup]]: [[2015 Saudi Super Cup|2015]]\n*[[Saudi Crown Prince Cup]]: [[2015\u201316 Saudi Crown Prince Cup|2015\u201316]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{NFT player|pid=15590}}\n\n{{Panathinaikos F.C. squad}}\n{{Superleague Greece managers}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards\n|bg = Gold\n|fg = Black\n|bordercolor = \n|list1 =\n{{Greek Cup top scorers}}\n{{Super League Greece manager of the year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{AEL F.C. managers}}\n{{AEK Athens F.C. managers}}\n{{Atromitos F.C. managers}}\n{{PAOK F.C. managers}}\n{{APOEL FC managers}}\n{{Al-Hilal FC managers}}\n{{Al-Sharjah SCC managers}}\n{{Panathinaikos F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donis, Giorgos}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\