{"title_page": "List of countries by hospital beds", "text_new": "[[File:Hospital-beds-per-1000-people.png|thumb|upright=1.6|Hospital beds per 1000 people in 2013]]\n{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of countries by [[hospital bed]]s''' per 1000 or 100,000 people, as published by the local governments, international organisation ([[OECD]], [[E.U.]]), academic sources or others. The number of beds per people is an important indicator of the [[health care]] system of a country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Health Care Resources|url=http://stats.oecd.org/index.aspx?DataSetCode=HEALTH_REAC#|website=stats.oecd.org|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref> The basic measure focus on all hospital beds, which are variously split and occupied. The classic hospital beds are also called curative beds. For severe patients with risk of organ(s) failure, patients are provided [[intensive care unit]] beds (aka ICU bed) or critical care beds (CCB).\n\nPoorer countries base capacity is at ~0.1 equipped ICU bed per 100,000 citizens.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bradley|first=Jane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/09/world/coronavirus-equipment-rich-poor.html|title=In Scramble for Coronavirus Supplies, Rich Countries Push Poor Aside|date=2020-04-09|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murthy|first=Srinivas|last2=Leligdowicz|first2=Aleksandra|last3=Adhikari|first3=Neill K. J.|date=2015-01-24|title=Intensive Care Unit Capacity in Low-Income Countries: A Systematic Review|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4305307/|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=10|issue=1|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0116949|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4305307|pmid=25617837}}</ref>  \n\nAmong OECD countries, curative beds' occupancy rate average was 75%, from 94.9% (Ireland) to 61.6% (Greece), with half of the OECD's nation between 70% and 80%.<ref name=\"oecd_beds-2020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/social-issues-migration-health/health-at-a-glance-2019_4dd50c09-en|title=Health at a Glance 2019: OECD Indicators, 9. Health care activities : Hospital beds and discharges rates.|last=|first=|date=|website=www.oecd-ilibrary.org|pages=194-195|language=en|doi=10.1787/4dd50c09-en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, European nations, most of them also part of OECD, had an aggregated total of 2,070,000 acute beds and 73,585 (2.8%{{clarification|date=March 2020}}) critical care beds (CCB) or 11.5CCB/100,000 inhabitants.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\" /> Germany had 29.2, Portugal 4.2.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\">{{cite journal|last=Rhodes|first=A.|last2=Ferdinande|first2=P.|last3=Flaatten|first3=H.|last4=Guidet|first4=B.|last5=Metnitz|first5=P. G.|last6=Moreno|first6=R. P.|date=2012-10-01|title=The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8|journal=Intensive Care Medicine|language=en|volume=38|issue=10|pages=1647\u20131653|doi=10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8|issn=1432-1238}}</ref>\n[[Aging population]] leads to increased demand for CCB and difficulties to satisfy it, while both quantity of CCB and availability are poorly documented.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\" />\n\n== 2020 coronavirus pandemic and hospital bed capacity ==\n{{Main|COVID-19 related shortages}}\n<!-- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- \n<!-- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- \n\nIMPORTANT!\nThis present section is temporary.\nIf you want to add content , please go to [[COVID-19 related shortages]]\nMain expansion is now on [[COVID-19 related shortages]].\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- \n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- -->\n[[File:Clinicians in Intensive Care Unit.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|A patient and clinicians in an [[intensive care unit]]]]\nThe availability of CCB-ICU beds,<ref>{{cite news|last=Srivastava|first=Ranjana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/17/now-more-than-ever-we-have-to-be-honest-about-intensive-care-beds|title=Now more than ever, we have to be honest about intensive care beds {{!}} Ranjana Srivastava|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[mechanical ventilation]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kliff|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus.html|title=There Aren\u2019t Enough Ventilators to Cope With the Coronavirus|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2020-03-18|last2=Satariano|first2=Adam|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Silver-Greenberg|first3=Jessica|last4=Kulish|first4=Nicholas}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daugherty Biddison|first=E. Lee|last2=Faden|first2=Ruth|last3=Gwon|first3=Howard S.|last4=Mareiniss|first4=Darren P.|last5=Regenberg|first5=Alan C.|last6=Schoch-Spana|first6=Monica|last7=Schwartz|first7=Jack|last8=Toner|first8=Eric S.|date=2019-04-01|title=Too Many Patients\u2026A Framework to Guide Statewide Allocation of Scarce Mechanical Ventilation During Disasters|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012369218325650|journal=Chest|language=en|volume=155|issue=4|pages=848\u2013854|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2018.09.025|issn=0012-3692}}</ref> and [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] devices<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ronco|first=Claudio|last2=Navalesi|first2=Paolo|last3=Vincent|first3=Jean Louis|date=2020-03-01|title=Coronavirus epidemic: preparing for extracorporeal organ support in intensive care|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanres/article/PIIS2213-2600(20)30060-6/abstract|journal=The Lancet Respiratory Medicine|language=English|volume=8|issue=3|pages=240\u2013241|doi=10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30060-6|issn=2213-2600|pmid=32035509}}</ref> generally closely associated with hospital beds has been described as a critical bottleneck in responding to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. The lack of such devices dramatically raises the mortality rate of COVID-19.\n\nIn early March, the UK government supported a strategy to develop natural [[herd immunity]], drawing sharp criticism from medical personnel and researchers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/u-k-realized-its-coronavirus-plan-could-kill-over-100-000.html|title=U.K. Only Grasped in the \u2018Last Few Days\u2019 It Had the Exact Wrong Coronavirus Plan|last=Stieb|first=Matt|date=2020-03-16|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref> Various forecasts by [[Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team]], made public on March 16th, suggested that the peak number of cases in the UK would require between 100 and 225 CCBs / 100,000 inhabitants,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |last=Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team|first=|date=2020-03-16|title=Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID19 mortality and healthcare demand|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|doi=|via=}}</ref> if proper mitigation or no mitigation strategies are put into force, respectively. These requirements would both exceed the UK's current capacities of 6.6<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\" />\u201314<ref name=\":0\" /> CCB / 100,000 inhabitants. In the best case scenario, the peak caseload would require 7.5 times the current number of available ICU beds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Batchelor|first=George|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/hospitals-could-need-75-times-number-critical-care-beds-treat/|title=Hospitals could need 7.5 times the number of critical care beds to treat virus patients|date=2020-03-15|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2020-03-17|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Around March 16th, the UK government changed trajectory toward a more standard mitigation/suppression strategy.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nIn [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], around March 15th, the [[Grand Est]] region was the first to express the scarcity of CCB limiting its handling of the crisis.<ref>https://www.europe1.fr/sante/coronavirus-dans-le-grand-est-pratiquement-tous-les-lits-de-reanimation-sont-occupes-3955371.amp</ref> [[Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance-publique H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]] (AP-HP), which manages most hospitals in the French capital area (~10 million inhabitants), reported the need for 3,000\u20134,000 ICUs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/17/covid-19-des-milliers-de-lits-de-reanimation-necessaires-dans-les-hopitaux-parisiens_6033380_3244.html|title=Covid-19 : l\u2019AP-HP s\u2019attend \u00e0 faire face \u00e0 une vague d\u2019hospitalisation bien plus haute que pr\u00e9vu|date=2020-03-17|work=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=2020-03-17|language=fr}}</ref> Current capacity is reported to be between 1500<ref name=\":1\" /> and 350,<ref>See [[:fr:Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]].</ref> depending on the source. \n\nIn Europe, the company [[L\u00f6wenstein Medical]] producing 1500 ICU-level ventilators and 20,000 home-level ventilator per year for France alone, pointed out of the current high demand and production shortage. Based in Germany, all their components are European and not relying on Chinese supply chains. As for production ramp up, the company has increased the production of mobile ventilators, that are more basic and can be assembled in half an hour, yet able to support patients through [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/l-interview-eco/coronavirus-la-demande-en-ventilateurs-et-respirateurs-artificiels-est-devenue-colossale-explique-un-specialiste-dans-le-materiel-medical_3849549.html|title=Coronavirus : la demande en ventilateurs et respirateurs artificiels est devenue \"colossale\", explique un sp\u00e9cialiste dans le mat\u00e9riel m\u00e9dical|date=2020-03-17|website=Franceinfo|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], in March 2020 the German government ordered 16.500 units for ventilation and intubation from two German companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noz.de/deutschland-welt/wirtschaft/artikel/2017949/loewenstein-medical-firma-aus-rheinland-pfalz-liefert-beatmungsgeraete|title=L\u00f6wenstein Medical in Rheinland-Pfalz: Wichtiger Auftrag: Diese deutsche Firma soll neue Beatmungsger\u00e4te liefern|last=|first=|date=|website=www.noz.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> - According to the company spokesman, a second bottleneck is the number of available medical staff, trained for such medical devices.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Numbers ==\n{{see also|Mechanical ventilation|Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation#The number of ECMOs by countries and territories}}\nCountries in ''italics'' are non-OECD countries.\n{{Hospital beds by country}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons cats|Hospital beds|Medical beds}}\n* [[Hospital bed]]\n* [[Mechanical ventilation]]\n* [[List of countries by life expectancy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|data}}\n{{Quality of life country lists}}\n[[Category:Beds]]\n[[Category:Health by country|Hospital beds]]\n[[Category:International rankings|Hospital beds, OECD]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Hospital-beds-per-1000-people.png|thumb|upright=1.6|Hospital beds per 1000 people in 2013]]\n{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of countries by [[hospital bed]]s''' per 