-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, European nations, most of them also part of OECD, had an aggregated total of 2,070,000 acute beds and 73,585 (2.8%{{clarification|date=March 2020}}) critical care beds (CCB) or 11.5CCB/100,000 inhabitants.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\" /> Germany had 29.2, Portugal 4.2.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\">{{cite journal|last=Rhodes|first=A.|last2=Ferdinande|first2=P.|last3=Flaatten|first3=H.|last4=Guidet|first4=B.|last5=Metnitz|first5=P. G.|last6=Moreno|first6=R. P.|date=2012-10-01|title=The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe|url=https://doi.org/10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8|journal=Intensive Care Medicine|language=en|volume=38|issue=10|pages=1647\u20131653|doi=10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8|issn=1432-1238}}</ref>\n[[Aging population]] leads to increased demand for CCB and difficulties to satisfy it, while both quantity of CCB and availability are poorly documented.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\" />\n\nBut India has been facilitated to defeat corona .. it's because of Modi Government . Indian people no need to worry about they health and safety .\n\n== 2020 coronavirus pandemic and hospital bed capacity ==\n{{Main|COVID-19 related shortages}}\n<!-- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- \n<!-- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- \n\nIMPORTANT!\nThis present section is temporary.\nIf you want to add content , please go to [[COVID-19 related shortages]]\nMain expansion is now on [[COVID-19 related shortages]].\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- \n---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- -->\n[[File:Clinicians in Intensive Care Unit.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|A patient and clinicians in an [[intensive care unit]]]]\nThe availability of CCB-ICU beds,<ref>{{cite news|last=Srivastava|first=Ranjana|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/17/now-more-than-ever-we-have-to-be-honest-about-intensive-care-beds|title=Now more than ever, we have to be honest about intensive care beds {{!}} Ranjana Srivastava|date=2020-03-16|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[mechanical ventilation]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kliff|first=Sarah|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/business/ventilator-shortage-coronavirus.html|title=There Aren\u2019t Enough Ventilators to Cope With the Coronavirus|date=2020-03-18|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2020-03-18|last2=Satariano|first2=Adam|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Silver-Greenberg|first3=Jessica|last4=Kulish|first4=Nicholas}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daugherty Biddison|first=E. Lee|last2=Faden|first2=Ruth|last3=Gwon|first3=Howard S.|last4=Mareiniss|first4=Darren P.|last5=Regenberg|first5=Alan C.|last6=Schoch-Spana|first6=Monica|last7=Schwartz|first7=Jack|last8=Toner|first8=Eric S.|date=2019-04-01|title=Too Many Patients\u2026A Framework to Guide Statewide Allocation of Scarce Mechanical Ventilation During Disasters|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012369218325650|journal=Chest|language=en|volume=155|issue=4|pages=848\u2013854|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2018.09.025|issn=0012-3692}}</ref> and [[Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] devices<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ronco|first=Claudio|last2=Navalesi|first2=Paolo|last3=Vincent|first3=Jean Louis|date=2020-03-01|title=Coronavirus epidemic: preparing for extracorporeal organ support in intensive care|url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanres/article/PIIS2213-2600(20)30060-6/abstract|journal=The Lancet Respiratory Medicine|language=English|volume=8|issue=3|pages=240\u2013241|doi=10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30060-6|issn=2213-2600|pmid=32035509}}</ref> generally closely associated with hospital beds has been described as a critical bottleneck in responding to the ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. The lack of such devices dramatically raises the mortality rate of COVID-19.\n\nIn early March, the UK government supported a strategy to develop natural [[herd immunity]], drawing sharp criticism from medical personnel and researchers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/u-k-realized-its-coronavirus-plan-could-kill-over-100-000.html|title=U.K. Only Grasped in the \u2018Last Few Days\u2019 It Had the Exact Wrong Coronavirus Plan|last=Stieb|first=Matt|date=2020-03-16|website=Intelligencer|language=en-us|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref> Various forecasts by [[Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team]], made public on March 16th, suggested that the peak number of cases in the UK would require between 100 and 225 CCBs / 100,000 inhabitants,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |last=Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team|first=|date=2020-03-16|title=Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID19 mortality and healthcare demand|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|doi=|via=}}</ref> if proper mitigation or no mitigation strategies are put into force, respectively. These requirements would both exceed the UK's current capacities of 6.6<ref name=\"Rhodes2012a\" />\u201314<ref name=\":0\" /> CCB / 100,000 inhabitants. In the best case scenario, the peak caseload would require 7.5 times the current number of available ICU beds.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Batchelor|first=George|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/hospitals-could-need-75-times-number-critical-care-beds-treat/|title=Hospitals could need 7.5 times the number of critical care beds to treat virus patients|date=2020-03-15|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=2020-03-17|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Around March 16th, the UK government changed trajectory toward a more standard mitigation/suppression strategy.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nIn [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|France]], around March 15th, the [[Grand Est]] region was the first to express the scarcity of CCB limiting its handling of the crisis.<ref>https://www.europe1.fr/sante/coronavirus-dans-le-grand-est-pratiquement-tous-les-lits-de-reanimation-sont-occupes-3955371.amp</ref> [[Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance-publique H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]] (AP-HP), which manages most hospitals in the French capital area (~10 million inhabitants), reported the need for 3,000\u20134,000 ICUs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2020/03/17/covid-19-des-milliers-de-lits-de-reanimation-necessaires-dans-les-hopitaux-parisiens_6033380_3244.html|title=Covid-19 : l\u2019AP-HP s\u2019attend \u00e0 faire face \u00e0 une vague d\u2019hospitalisation bien plus haute que pr\u00e9vu|date=2020-03-17|work=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=2020-03-17|language=fr}}</ref> Current capacity is reported to be between 1500<ref name=\":1\" /> and 350,<ref>See [[:fr:Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris|Assistance Publique \u2013 H\u00f4pitaux de Paris]].</ref> depending on the source. \n\nIn Europe, the company [[L\u00f6wenstein Medical]] producing 1500 ICU-level ventilators and 20,000 home-level ventilator per year for France alone, pointed out of the current high demand and production shortage. Based in Germany, all their components are European and not relying on Chinese supply chains. As for production ramp up, the company has increased the production of mobile ventilators, that are more basic and can be assembled in half an hour, yet able to support patients through [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/l-interview-eco/coronavirus-la-demande-en-ventilateurs-et-respirateurs-artificiels-est-devenue-colossale-explique-un-specialiste-dans-le-materiel-medical_3849549.html|title=Coronavirus : la demande en ventilateurs et respirateurs artificiels est devenue \"colossale\", explique un sp\u00e9cialiste dans le mat\u00e9riel m\u00e9dical|date=2020-03-17|website=Franceinfo|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], in March 2020 the German government ordered 16.500 units for ventilation and intubation from two German companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noz.de/deutschland-welt/wirtschaft/artikel/2017949/loewenstein-medical-firma-aus-rheinland-pfalz-liefert-beatmungsgeraete|title=L\u00f6wenstein Medical in Rheinland-Pfalz: Wichtiger Auftrag: Diese deutsche Firma soll neue Beatmungsger\u00e4te liefern|last=|first=|date=|website=www.noz.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> - According to the company spokesman, a second bottleneck is the number of available medical staff, trained for such medical devices.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Numbers ==\n{{see also|Mechanical ventilation|Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation#The number of ECMOs by countries and territories}}\nCountries in ''italics'' are non-OECD countries.\n{{Hospital beds by country}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons cats|Hospital beds|Medical beds}}\n* [[Hospital bed]]\n* [[Mechanical ventilation]]\n* [[List of countries by life expectancy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|data}}\n{{Quality of life country lists}}\n[[Category:Beds]]\n[[Category:Health by country|Hospital beds]]\n[[Category:International rankings|Hospital beds, OECD]]\n", "name_user": "Rabbitflyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed unsourced POV.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_hospital_beds"}
{"title_page": "Edwin Edwards (New Zealand politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Edwin Edwards''' (5 April 1862 &ndash; 31 May 1909) was a New Zealand businessman, local politician, newspaper proprietor and editor, balladeer. He was born in [[Camberwell]], [[Surrey]], England on 5 April 1862.<ref name=\"DNZB Edwards\">{{DNZB|last=O'Brien|first=Brian|id=2e5|title=Edwards, Edwin|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> He unsuccessfully contested the {{NZ electorate link|Ohinemuri}} electorate in the {{NZ election link|1896}} against [[Alfred Cadman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The General Election |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18961223.2.28.8 |accessdate=8 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Auckland Star]] |date=23 December 1896 |volume=XXVII |issue=305 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, Edwin}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:New Zealand writers]]\n[[Category:People from Camberwell]]\n[[Category:Unsuccessful candidates in the 1896 New Zealand general election]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-politician-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-writer-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2016}}\n'''Edwin Edwards''' (5 April 1862 &ndash; 31 May 1909) was a New Zealand businessman, local politician, newspaper proprietor and editor, balladeer. He was born in [[Camberwell]], [[Surrey]], England on 5 April 1862.<ref name=\"DNZB Edwards\">{{DNZB|last=O'Brien|first=Brian|id=2e5|title=Edwards, Edwin|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> He unsuccessfully contested the {{NZ electorate link|Ohinemuri}} electorate in the {{NZ election link|1896}} against [[Alfred Cadman]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The General Election |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18961223.2.28.8 |accessdate=8 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Auckland Star]] |date=23 December 1896 |volume=XXVII |issue=305 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edwards, Edwin}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:New Zealand writers]]\n[[Category:People from Camberwell]]\n[[Category:Unsuccessful candidates in the 1896 New Zealand general election]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand politicians]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-politician-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-writer-stub}}\n{{NewZealand-business-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edwin_Edwards_(New_Zealand_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Rambo III", "text_new": "{{About|the 1988 film|the video game|Rambo III (video game)}}\n{{short description|1988 US action film directed by Peter MacDonald}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rambo III\n| image          = Rambo3poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter MacDonald (director)|Peter MacDonald]]\n| producer       = [[Buzz Feitshans]]\n| writer     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sylvester Stallone]]\n* [[Sheldon Lettich]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|[[John Rambo]]|[[David Morrell]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Sylvester Stallone\n* [[Richard Crenna]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| cinematography = John Stanier\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* James Symons\n* Andrew London\n* O. Nicholas Brown\n}}\n| studio         = [[Carolco Pictures]]<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/59082|title=Rambo III (1988)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[TriStar Pictures]]<ref name=\"AFI\" />\n| released       = {{Film date|1988|05|25|United States}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 101:33--><ref name=\"bbfc\"/>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $58\u201363 million<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Sheldon |last2=Neale |first2=Stephen |title=Epics, spectacles, and blockbusters: a Hollywood history |year=2010 |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |isbn=978-0-8143-3008-1 |pages=239\u2013240 |quote=''Rambo III'' (1988) cost a then-record $58 million.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Patrick |last=Robertson |title=Guinness Book of Movie Facts and Feats |year=1991 |publisher=[[Abbeville Press]] |isbn=9781558592360 |page=33}}</ref>\n| gross          = $189 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''Rambo III''''' is a 1988 American [[action film]] directed by [[Peter MacDonald (director)|Peter MacDonald]] and co-written by [[Sylvester Stallone]], who also reprises his role as [[Vietnam War]] veteran [[John Rambo]]. A sequel to ''[[Rambo: First Blood Part II]]'' (1985), it is the third installment in the [[Rambo (franchise)|''Rambo'' franchise]], followed by ''[[Rambo (2008 film)|Rambo]]''. It was the last film to feature [[Richard Crenna]] as [[Sam Trautman|Colonel Sam Trautman]] before his death in 2003.\n\nThe film depicts fictional events during the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]. In the film, Rambo sets out on a dangerous journey to [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]] in order to rescue his former military commander and his longtime best friend Colonel Trautman from the hands of an extremely powerful and ruthless [[Soviet Army]] colonel who is bent on killing both Trautman and Rambo, as he helps lead the Soviet armed forces and their mission: Conquering Afghanistan.\n\n''Rambo III'' was released worldwide on May 25, 1988, and grossed $189 million at the box office. With a production budget of between $58 and $63 million, ''Rambo III'' was the most expensive film ever made at the time.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Plot summaries are usually between 400-700 words. Please see WP:FILMPLOT for more information. -->\nThree years [[Rambo: First Blood Part II|after the events in Vietnam]], [[Colonel Sam Trautman]] visits his old friend and ally [[John Rambo]] in Thailand. He explains that he is putting together a mercenary team for a [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]]-sponsored mission to supply the [[Mujahideen]] and other tribes as they try to repel the Soviet Army in [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]]. Despite being shown photos of civilians suffering at the hands of the Soviet military, Rambo refuses to join, as he is tired of fighting. Trautman proceeds anyway and is ambushed by enemy forces near the border, resulting in all of his men being killed. Trautman is captured and sent to a large mountain base to be interrogated by Soviet Colonel Zaysen and his henchman Sergeant Kourov.\n\nEmbassy official [[Robert Griggs]] informs Rambo of Col. Trautman's capture but refuses to approve a rescue mission for fear of drawing the United States into the war. Aware that Trautman will die otherwise, Rambo gets permission to undertake a solo rescue on the condition that he will be disavowed in the event of capture or death. Rambo immediately flies to [[Peshawar]], Pakistan, where he intends to convince arms dealer Mousa Ghani to bring him to [[Khost]], the town closest to the Soviet base where Trautman is held captive.\n\nThe [[Mujahideen]] in the village, led by chieftain Masoud, hesitate to help Rambo free Trautman. Meanwhile, a Soviet informant in Ghani's employ informs the Soviets, who send two attack helicopters to destroy the village. Though Rambo manages to destroy one of them with a turret, the rebels refuse to aid him any further. Aided only by Mousa and a young boy named Hamid, Rambo attacks the base and inflicts significant damage before being forced to retreat. Hamid, as well as Rambo, are wounded during the battle and Rambo sends him and Mousa away before resuming his infiltration.\n\nSkillfully evading base security, Rambo reaches Trautman just as he is about to be tortured with a [[flamethrower]]. He and Trautman rescue several other prisoners and hijack a [[Mil Mi-24|Hind]] [[Gunship|gunship helicopter]] to escape the base. The helicopter is damaged during takeoff and quickly crashes, forcing the escapees to flee across the sand on foot. An [[attack helicopter]] pursues Rambo and Trautman to a nearby cave, where Rambo destroys it with an explosive arrow. A furious Zaysen sends [[Spetsnaz]] commandos under Kourov to kill them, but they are quickly routed and killed. An injured Kourov attacks Rambo with his bare hands, but is overcome and killed.\n\nAs Rambo and Trautman make their way to the [[Durand Line|Pakistani border]], Zaysen and his forces surround them. But before the duo are overwhelmed, Masoud's Mujahideen forces attack the Soviets in a surprise cavalry charge. Despite being wounded, Rambo takes control of a tank and uses it to attack Zaysen's Hind gunship in a head-on battle with both vehicles firing high-calibre machine gun rounds, Rambo firing the tank's main gun and Zaysen unleashing volleys of the Hind's high explosive rockets and missiles. The final charge sees the two vehicles collide, but Rambo survives after firing the tank's main gun after colliding with Zaysen's Hind. At the end of the battle, Rambo and Trautman say goodbye to the Mujahideen and leave Afghanistan.\n\n==Cast==\n{{main|List of Rambo characters}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[Sylvester Stallone]] as [[John Rambo|John J. Rambo]]\n* [[Richard Crenna]] as [[Sam Trautman|Colonel Samuel \"Sam\" R. Trautman]]\n* [[Kurtwood Smith]] as [[Robert Griggs]]\n* [[Marc de Jonge]] as Colonel Alexei Zaysen\n* [[Sasson Gabai]] as Mousa Ghani\n* Doudi Shoua as Hamid\n* [[Spiros Foc\u00e1s|Spiros Focas]] as Masoud\n* Randy Raney as Sergeant Kourov\n* [[Marcus Gilbert (actor)|Marcus Gilbert]] as Tomask\n* [[Alon Abutbul]] as Nissem\n* Mahmoud Assadollahi as Rahim\n* [[Yosef Shiloach|Yosef Shiloah]] as Khalid\n* Shaby Ben-Aroya as Uri \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\nSylvester Stallone later said his original premise of the film \"was more in keeping with the theme of ''[[Tears of the Sun]]'', but set in Afghanistan.\"<ref name=\"sly\"/>\n\n''[[Bullitt]]'' and ''[[Red Heat (1988 film)|Red Heat]]'' scribe [[Harry Kleiner]] was hired to write a draft, but his script was rejected by Stallone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-05-10/entertainment/ca-6236_1_harry-kleiner|title=Son Of 'Bullitt'|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske|date=May 10, 1987|website=Articles.latimes.com|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref>\n \nSeveral weeks into filming, many of the film's crew were fired including the [[director of photography]] and director [[Russell Mulcahy]]. Stallone:\n\n<blockquote>The canvas of this movie is so large you have to constantly think 10 scenes ahead. You can't wing it. They didn't go into the [[Battle of Waterloo]] not knowing what their strategy would be. Well, this movie is kind of like a cinematic warfare. We have a huge cast and crew (more than 250 people) and tough locations to deal with. Everyone and everything has to coordinate.<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/1987-09-22/entertainment/ca-9679_1_rambo-iii 'Rambo Iii' Gets Back On The Track In Israel ''Los Angeles Times'' September 22, 1987|PAT H. BROESKE]</ref></blockquote>\n\nSome critics noted that the timing of the movie, with its unabashedly anti-Soviet tone, ran afoul of the opening of [[Communism]] to the West under [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], which had already changed the image of the Soviet Union to a substantial degree by the time the movie was finished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.exile.ru/articles/detail.php?ARTICLE_ID=10145&IBLOCK_ID=35|title=Preview Review: Rambo IV|website=Exile.ru|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Pre-production===\n<blockquote>He went to Israel two weeks before me with the task of casting two dozen vicious looking Russian troops. These men were {{sic|suppose}} to make your blood run cold. When I arrived on the set, what I saw was two dozen blond, blue-eyed pretty boys that resembled rejects from a surfing contest. Needless to say Rambo is not afraid of a little competition but being attacked by third rate male models could be an enemy that could overwhelm him. I explained my disappointment to Russell and he totally disagreed, so I asked him and his chiffon army to move on.<ref name=\"sly\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aintitcool.com/node/35350|title=Day 3 - Stallone guts some more questions and lets the answers spill out!|website=Aintitcool.com|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nMulcahy was replaced by [[Peter MacDonald (director)|Peter MacDonald]], a veteran second unit director. It was MacDonald's first film as director but he was very experienced and had directed the second unit action sequences in ''[[Rambo: First Blood Part II]]''. MacDonald later said, \"I tried very hard to change the Rambo character a bit and make him a vulnerable and humorous person, I failed totally.\"<ref name=\"peter\">[http://filmint.nu/?p=10089 David Ellis, \"Peter MacDonald: The Man Who Failed to Change Rambo\", ''Film International'' 20 November 2013]</ref> \"I knew instinctively what was a good and bad shot,\" he added. \"Stallone knew his character because it was his third outing as Rambo. I wasn't shooting [[Shakespeare]] and at times it was hard to take it seriously.\"<ref name=\"peter\"/> MacDonald shot the stick fighting sequence in [[Bangkok]] himself using a [[Hand-held camera|handheld camera]].<ref name=\"peter\"/>\n\nThe character Masoud, played by Greek actor Spiros Foc\u00e1s, was named after Mujahideen commander [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]] who fought the USSR and later the [[Taliban]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-05-27-ca-3994-story.html|title=Rambo III}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe film was shot in Israel, Thailand, and [[Arizona]]. MacDonald:\n\n<blockquote>There were so many restrictions in Israel, where you could and couldn't shoot. The producers and Stallone decided they would go back to Arizona where they had looked long before I was on the film. There was a group there called the re-enactors. We had around two hundred and fifty of these guys who re-enact the [[American Civil War|[American] civil war]]. They were called on to do fight sequences, which they loved.<ref name=\"peter\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Rambo III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Film\n| artist     = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1988\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = \n| label      = \n| producer   = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| prev_title = [[Rent-a-Cop|Rent-a-Cop: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[Criminal Law (film)|Criminal Law: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\nAn extensive film score was written by [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning American composer [[Jerry Goldsmith]], conducting the [[Hungarian State Opera|Hungarian State Opera Orchestra]]; however, much of it was not used. Instead, much of the music Goldsmith penned for the previous installment was recycled. The original album, released by [[Scotti Bros.]], contained only a portion of the new music as well as three songs, only one of which was used in the film ([[Bill Medley]]'s version of \"He Ain't Heavy, He's My Brother\", played over the end credits).\n\n# It Is Our Destiny \u2013 Bill Medley (4:30)\n# Preparations (4:58)\n# Afghanistan (2:35)\n# The Game (2:23)\n# Another Time (3:54)\n# He Ain't Heavy, He's My Brother \u2013 Bill Medley (4:30)\n# Aftermath (2:42)\n# Questions (3:34)\n# The Bridge - [[Giorgio Moroder]] featuring Joe Pizullo (3:59)\n# Final Battle (4:47)\n\nA more complete 75-minute version of the score was later released by [[Intrada Records|Intrada]].\n# Another Time (3:58)\n# Preparations (06:21)\n# The Money (0:52)\n# I'm Used To It (1:00)\n# Peshawar (1:12)\n# Afghanistan (2:38)\n# Questions (3:37)\n# Then I'll Die (3:34)\n# The Game (2:25)\n# Flaming Village (4:07)\n# The Aftermath (2:44)\n# Night Entry (3:58)\n# Under And Over (2:55)\n# Night Fight (6:50)\n# First Aid (2:46)\n# The Long Climb (3:25)\n# Going Down (1:52)\n# The Cave (3:31)\n# The Boot (1:53)\n# You Did It, John (1:08)\n# The Showdown (1:26)\n# Final Battle (4:50)\n# I'll Stay (9:00)\n\n==Release==\n\n===Box office===\n''Rambo III'' opened in the United States on May 25, 1988 at 2,562 theatres in its opening weekend (the four-day [[Memorial Day]] weekend), ranking #2 behind ''[[Crocodile Dundee II]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= WEEKEND BOX OFFICE : Crocodile Swamps 'Rambo'; Hanks' 'Big' Hit |newspaper= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1988-06-14|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1988-06-14/entertainment/ca-4175_1_big-business|accessdate=2011-01-01|first=Nina|last=Easton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ad4cAAAAIBAJ&pg=3841,1104602 | title='Croc' devours 'Rambo' in first week in theaters | first=Ed | last=Blank | newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Press]] | accessdate=29 October 2010 }}</ref> Overall, the film grossed $53,715,611 domestically and then took $135,300,000 overseas, giving ''Rambo III'' a box office total of $189,015,611.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rambo3.htm|title=Rambo III (1988) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref> The film underperformed at the box-office.<ref>{{cite news|title= Roger Rabbit' Hops to Box-Office Top; 'Coming to America' Hits 2nd|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=1989-01-05|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1989-01-05/entertainment/ca-271_1_box-office-information/2|accessdate=2010-10-29|first=Nina J.|last=Easton}}</ref>\n\nAudiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film scored a 37% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 34 reviews and with an average rating of 4.53/10. The sites critical consensus states that \"''Rambo III'' finds its justice-dispensing hero far from the thoughtful drama that marked the franchise's beginning -- and just as far from quality action thriller entertainment.\"<ref>{{Rotten tomatoes|id=rambo_iii}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the film a rating of 36 out of 100 based on 15 critic reviews, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Metacritic film|id=rambo-iii}}</ref>\n\nProminent critics [[Gene Siskel]] and [[Roger Ebert]] were split on ''Rambo III'', with Siskel awarding the film \"thumbs up\", and Ebert declaring \"thumbs down\" for those expecting more out of ''Rambo III''. Ebert did, however, give \"thumbs up\" to fans, saying the film was entertaining and that it \"delivers the goods\".\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' took a dim view of the film.<ref name=\"Maslin\"/>\n\nIn [[West Germany]], the [[Deutsche Film- und Medienbewertung (FBW)]], a government film rating office whose ratings influence financial support to filmmakers, earned criticism after it awarded a \"worthwhile\" rating (in German: ''wertvoll'') to ''Rambo III''.<ref>https://www.fbw-filmbewertung.com/film/rambo_3</ref>\n\nThe 1990 ''[[The Guinness Book of World Records]]'' deemed ''Rambo III'' the most violent film ever made, with 221 acts of violence, at least 70 explosions, and over 108 characters killed on-screen.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} However, the body count of the fourth film in the series, ''[[Rambo (2008 film)|Rambo]]'', surpassed that record, with 236 kills.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} The [[Mi-24|Mi-24 Hind-D]] helicopters seen in the film are in fact modified [[A\u00e9rospatiale]] [[A\u00e9rospatiale Puma|SA 330 Puma]] transport helicopters with fabricated bolt-on wings similar to the real Hind-Ds which were mainly used in the former [[Eastern Bloc]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} The other helicopter depicted is a slightly reshaped [[Aerospatiale Gazelle]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nSome have claimed that the dedication at the end of the film has been altered at various points in response to the [[September 11 attacks]]. Specifically it is claimed that the dedication was (at one point) \"to the brave Mujahideen fighters\" and then later changed to \"to the gallant people of Afghanistan\".{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} However, reviews of the film upon its release and later publications show that the film was always dedicated \"to the gallant people of Afghanistan\".<ref name=\"Maslin\">{{cite news|title= Reviews/Film; Stallone's 'Rambo III,' Globe-Trotting Cowboy For the 80's Audience |work= The New York Times|date=1988-05-25|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/25/movies/reviews-film-stallone-s-rambo-iii-globe-trotting-cowboy-for-the-80-s-audience.html|accessdate=2010-10-29|first=Janet|last=Maslin}}</ref><ref>''The Civil War in Popular Culture'' (1996). Washington D.C.: The Smithsonian Institution. {{ISBN|1560986875}}, p.152.</ref><ref>''Vietnam war films: over 600 feature, made-for-TV, pilot, and short movies, 1939-1992, from the United States, Vietnam, France, Belgium, Australia, Hong Kong, South Africa, Great Britain, and other countries'' (1994). Mcfarland & Co Inc Pub. {{ISBN|0899507816}}, p. 355.</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=8|[[Golden Raspberry Award|Razzie Award]]\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Sylvester Stallone]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Sheldon Lettich]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]]\n|[[Richard Crenna]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]]\n|[[Mario Kassar]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Buzz Feitshans]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Andrew G. Vajna]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n|[[Peter MacDonald (film director)|Peter MacDonald]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Home media==\n''Rambo III'' was released on [[DVD]] on November 23, 2004, and a [[Blu-ray|Blu-Ray]] release followed on May 23, 2008. ''Rambo III'' was released on [[4K resolution|4K]] [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|UHD Blu-Ray]] on November 13, 2018.\n\n===Cut version===\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], the original theatrical trailer released worldwide by Columbia Pictures Industries, Inc. was rejected, but three versions appear on [[VHS]], DVD and Blu-ray and original theatrical release. The [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]] rated the theatrical release 18 and later video releases rated 15. They also cut between two seconds and 65 seconds of the original film's runtime.<ref name=\"bbfc\">{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/rambo-iii-0 |title=BBFC Cinema Rating, 1988|website=Bbfc.co.uk|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Some later video releases almost tripled the cuts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/rambo-iii |title=BBFC Video Rating, 1989|website=Bbfc.co.uk|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Sequel===\n{{Main|Rambo (2008 film)}}\nA sequel titled ''Rambo'', was released in 2008.\n\n===Novelization===\n[[David Morrell]], author of ''[[First Blood (novel)|First Blood]]'', the novel the first ''Rambo'' film is based on, wrote a novelization called ''Rambo III''.\n\n===Comic books===\nA comic book adaptation of the film was published by [[Blackthorne Publishing]].<ref>{{gcdb issue|id=321002|title=Blackthorne Publishing: ''Rambo III''}}</ref><ref>{{comicbookdb|type=issue|id=109940|title=Blackthorne Publishing: ''Rambo III''}}</ref>  Blackthorne also published a 3D version of its ''Rambo III'' comic.\n\n===Video games===\nVarious companies released [[Rambo III (video game)|video games based on the film]], including [[Ocean Software]] and [[Taito]]. In 1990, Sega released its own game based on the film for the [[Master System]] and [[Sega Genesis|Genesis/Mega Drive]]. [[Sega]] later adapted some of the battle scenes in the film for the 2008 arcade game ''[[Rambo (2008 video game)|Rambo]]''. In 2014 was released ''[[Rambo: The Video Game]]'', based on the first three ''Rambo'' films.\n\n===Other references===\n* In the film ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre 2]]'', the character of [[Chop Top]] jokes that the recording of one chainsaw murder sounds like \"the ''Rambo III'' soundtrack\", although at that time, there had only been two ''Rambo'' films.\n* In the film ''[[Twins (1988 film)|Twins]]'', [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]]'s character is seen looking at the poster of ''Rambo III'' featuring Stallone, where he compares his biceps to Stallone's, but waves it off with a smile while shaking his head and walks away.\n* In the film ''[[Hot Shots! Part Deux]]'', the protagonist Topper Harley ([[Charlie Sheen]]) is a parody of John Rambo and the plot of the film is the same as ''Rambo III'', which involves Harley rescuing his mentor, Col. Denton Walters (Richard Crenna, parodying his character from the ''Rambo'' franchise).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0095956}}\n* {{amg movie|40200}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=87653}}\n* {{AFI film|id=59082|title=Rambo III}}\n* {{mojo title|rambo3}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|rambo_iii}}\n* {{metacritic film|rambo-iii}}\n\n{{Rambo}}\n{{Sylvester Stallone}}\n{{Peter MacDonald}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rambo III}}\n[[Category:1988 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action films]]\n[[Category:1980s adventure films]]\n[[Category:1980s sequel films]]\n[[Category:1980s war films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action films]]\n[[Category:American anti-communist propaganda films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Carolco Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in Asia]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter MacDonald]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jerry Goldsmith]]\n[[Category:Films set in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Israel]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Rambo]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Sylvester Stallone]]\n[[Category:Soviet\u2013Afghan War films]]\n[[Category:Films about United States Army Special Forces]]\n[[Category:1988 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1988 film|the video game|Rambo III (video game)}}\n{{short description|1988 US action film directed by Peter MacDonald}}\n{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rambo III\n| image          = Rambo3poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter MacDonald (director)|Peter MacDonald]]\n| producer       = [[Buzz Feitshans]]\n| writer     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sylvester Stallone]]\n* [[Sheldon Lettich]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|[[John Rambo]]|[[David Morrell]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Sylvester Stallone\n* [[Richard Crenna]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| cinematography = John Stanier\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* James Symons\n* Andrew London\n* O. Nicholas Brown\n}}\n| studio         = [[Carolco Pictures]]<ref name=\"AFI\">{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/59082|title=Rambo III (1988)|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n| distributor    = [[TriStar Pictures]]<ref name=\"AFI\" />\n| released       = {{Film date|1988|05|25|United States}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 101:33--><ref name=\"bbfc\"/>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $58\u201363 million<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Hall |first1=Sheldon |last2=Neale |first2=Stephen |title=Epics, spectacles, and blockbusters: a Hollywood history |year=2010 |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |isbn=978-0-8143-3008-1 |pages=239\u2013240 |quote=''Rambo III'' (1988) cost a then-record $58 million.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Patrick |last=Robertson |title=Guinness Book of Movie Facts and Feats |year=1991 |publisher=[[Abbeville Press]] |isbn=9781558592360 |page=33}}</ref>\n| gross          = $189 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n}}\n'''''Rambo III''''' is a 1988 American [[action film]] directed by [[Peter MacDonald (director)|Peter MacDonald]] and co-written by [[Sylvester Stallone]], who also reprises his role as [[Vietnam War]] veteran [[John Rambo]]. A sequel to ''[[Rambo: First Blood Part II]]'' (1985), it is the third installment in the [[Rambo (franchise)|''Rambo'' franchise]], followed by ''[[Rambo (2008 film)|Rambo]]''. It was the last film to feature [[Richard Crenna]] as [[Sam Trautman|Colonel Sam Trautman]] before his death in 2003.\n\nThe film depicts fictional events during the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]. In the film, Rambo sets out on a dangerous journey to [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]] in order to rescue his former military commander and his longtime best friend Colonel Trautman from the hands of an extremely powerful and ruthless [[Soviet Army]] colonel who is bent on killing both Trautman and Rambo, as he helps lead the Soviet armed forces and their mission: Conquering Afghanistan.\n\n''Rambo III'' was released worldwide on May 25, 1988, and grossed $189 million at the box office. With a production budget of between $58 and $63 million, ''Rambo III'' was the most expensive film ever made at the time.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Plot summaries are usually between 400-700 words. Please see WP:FILMPLOT for more information. -->\nThree years [[Rambo: First Blood Part II|after the events in Vietnam]], [[Colonel Sam Trautman]] visits his old friend and ally [[John Rambo]] in Thailand. He explains that he is putting together a mercenary team for a [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]]-sponsored mission to supply the [[Mujahideen]] and other tribes as they try to repel the Soviet Army in [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]]. Despite being shown photos of civilians suffering at the hands of the Soviet military, Rambo refuses to join, as he is tired of fighting. Trautman proceeds anyway and is ambushed by enemy forces near the border, resulting in all of his men being killed. Trautman is captured and sent to a large mountain base to be interrogated by Soviet Colonel Zaysen and his henchman Sergeant Kourov.\n\nEmbassy official [[Robert Griggs]] informs Rambo of Col. Trautman's capture but refuses to approve a rescue mission for fear of drawing the United States into the war. Aware that Trautman will die otherwise, Rambo gets permission to undertake a solo rescue on the condition that he will be disavowed in the event of capture or death. Rambo immediately flies to [[Peshawar]], Pakistan, where he intends to convince arms dealer Mousa Ghani to bring him to [[Khost]], the town closest to the Soviet base where Trautman is held captive.\n\nThe [[Mujahideen]] in the village, led by chieftain Masoud, hesitate to help Rambo free Trautman. Meanwhile, a Soviet informant in Ghani's employ informs the Soviets, who send two attack helicopters to destroy the village. Though Rambo manages to destroy one of them with a turret, the rebels refuse to aid him any further. Aided only by Mousa and a young boy named Hamid, Rambo attacks the base and inflicts significant damage before being forced to retreat. Hamid, as well as Rambo, are wounded during the battle and Rambo sends him and Mousa away before resuming his infiltration.\n\nSkillfully evading base security, Rambo reaches Trautman just as he is about to be tortured with a [[flamethrower]]. He and Trautman rescue several other prisoners and hijack a [[Mil Mi-24|Hind]] [[Gunship|gunship helicopter]] to escape the base. The helicopter is damaged during takeoff and quickly crashes, forcing the escapees to flee across the sand on foot. An [[attack helicopter]] pursues Rambo and Trautman to a nearby cave, where Rambo destroys it with an explosive arrow. A furious Zaysen sends [[Spetsnaz]] commandos under Kourov to kill them, but they are quickly routed and killed. An injured Kourov attacks Rambo with his bare hands, but is overcome and killed.\n\nAs Rambo and Trautman make their way to the [[Durand Line|Pakistani border]], Zaysen and his forces surround them. But before the duo are overwhelmed, Masoud's Mujahideen forces attack the Soviets in a surprise cavalry charge. Despite being wounded, Rambo takes control of a tank and uses it to attack Zaysen's Hind gunship in a head-on battle with both vehicles firing high-calibre machine gun rounds, Rambo firing the tank's main gun and Zaysen unleashing volleys of the Hind's high explosive rockets and missiles. The final charge sees the two vehicles collide, but Rambo survives after firing the tank's main gun after colliding with Zaysen's Hind. At the end of the battle, Rambo and Trautman say goodbye to the Mujahideen and leave Afghanistan.\n\n==Cast==\n{{main|List of Rambo characters}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[Sylvester Stallone]] as [[John Rambo|John J. Rambo]]\n* [[Richard Crenna]] as [[Sam Trautman|Colonel Samuel \"Sam\" R. Trautman]]\n* [[Kurtwood Smith]] as [[Robert Griggs]]\n* [[Marc de Jonge]] as Colonel Alexei Zaysen\n* [[Sasson Gabai]] as Mousa Ghani\n* Doudi Shoua as Hamid\n* [[Spiros Foc\u00e1s|Spiros Focas]] as Masoud\n* Randy Raney as Sergeant Kourov\n* [[Marcus Gilbert (actor)|Marcus Gilbert]] as Tomask\n* [[Alon Abutbul]] as Nissem\n* Mahmoud Assadollahi as Rahim\n* [[Yosef Shiloach|Yosef Shiloah]] as Khalid\n* Shaby Ben-Aroya as Uri \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\nSylvester Stallone later said his original premise of the film \"was more in keeping with the theme of ''[[Tears of the Sun]]'', but set in Afghanistan.\"<ref name=\"sly\"/>\n\n''[[Bullitt]]'' and ''[[Red Heat (1988 film)|Red Heat]]'' scribe [[Harry Kleiner]] was hired to write a draft, but his script was rejected by Stallone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1987-05-10/entertainment/ca-6236_1_harry-kleiner|title=Son Of 'Bullitt'|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske|date=May 10, 1987|website=Articles.latimes.com|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref>\n \nSeveral weeks into filming, many of the film's crew were fired including the [[director of photography]] and director [[Russell Mulcahy]]. Stallone:\n\n<blockquote>The canvas of this movie is so large you have to constantly think 10 scenes ahead. You can't wing it. They didn't go into the [[Battle of Waterloo]] not knowing what their strategy would be. Well, this movie is kind of like a cinematic warfare. We have a huge cast and crew (more than 250 people) and tough locations to deal with. Everyone and everything has to coordinate.<ref>[https://articles.latimes.com/1987-09-22/entertainment/ca-9679_1_rambo-iii 'Rambo Iii' Gets Back On The Track In Israel ''Los Angeles Times'' September 22, 1987|PAT H. BROESKE]</ref></blockquote>\n\nSome critics noted that the timing of the movie, with its unabashedly anti-Soviet tone, ran afoul of the opening of [[Communism]] to the West under [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], which had already changed the image of the Soviet Union to a substantial degree by the time the movie was finished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.exile.ru/articles/detail.php?ARTICLE_ID=10145&IBLOCK_ID=35|title=Preview Review: Rambo IV|website=Exile.ru|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Pre-production===\n<blockquote>He went to Israel two weeks before me with the task of casting two dozen vicious looking Russian troops. These men were {{sic|suppose}} to make your blood run cold. When I arrived on the set, what I saw was two dozen blond, blue-eyed pretty boys that resembled rejects from a surfing contest. Needless to say Rambo is not afraid of a little competition but being attacked by third rate male models could be an enemy that could overwhelm him. I explained my disappointment to Russell and he totally disagreed, so I asked him and his chiffon army to move on.<ref name=\"sly\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aintitcool.com/node/35350|title=Day 3 - Stallone guts some more questions and lets the answers spill out!|website=Aintitcool.com|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nMulcahy was replaced by [[Peter MacDonald (director)|Peter MacDonald]], a veteran second unit director. It was MacDonald's first film as director but he was very experienced and had directed the second unit action sequences in ''[[Rambo: First Blood Part II]]''. MacDonald later said, \"I tried very hard to change the Rambo character a bit and make him a vulnerable and humorous person, I failed totally.\"<ref name=\"peter\">[http://filmint.nu/?p=10089 David Ellis, \"Peter MacDonald: The Man Who Failed to Change Rambo\", ''Film International'' 20 November 2013]</ref> \"I knew instinctively what was a good and bad shot,\" he added. \"Stallone knew his character because it was his third outing as Rambo. I wasn't shooting [[Shakespeare]] and at times it was hard to take it seriously.\"<ref name=\"peter\"/> MacDonald shot the stick fighting sequence in [[Bangkok]] himself using a [[Hand-held camera|handheld camera]].<ref name=\"peter\"/>\n\nThe character Masoud, played by Greek actor Spiros Foc\u00e1s, was named after Mujahideen commander [[Ahmad Shah Massoud]] who fought the USSR and later the [[Taliban]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1988-05-27-ca-3994-story.html|title=Rambo III}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe film was shot in Israel, Thailand, and [[Arizona]]. MacDonald:\n\n<blockquote>There were so many restrictions in Israel, where you could and couldn't shoot. The producers and Stallone decided they would go back to Arizona where they had looked long before I was on the film. There was a group there called the re-enactors. We had around two hundred and fifty of these guys who re-enact the [[American Civil War|[American] civil war]]. They were called on to do fight sequences, which they loved.<ref name=\"peter\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Music==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Rambo III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Film\n| artist     = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1988\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = \n| label      = \n| producer   = [[Jerry Goldsmith]]\n| prev_title = [[Rent-a-Cop|Rent-a-Cop: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 1987\n| next_title = [[Criminal Law (film)|Criminal Law: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 1988\n}}\n\nAn extensive film score was written by [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning American composer [[Jerry Goldsmith]], conducting the [[Hungarian State Opera|Hungarian State Opera Orchestra]]; however, much of it was not used. Instead, much of the music Goldsmith penned for the previous installment was recycled. The original album, released by [[Scotti Bros.]], contained only a portion of the new music as well as three songs, only one of which was used in the film ([[Bill Medley]]'s version of \"He Ain't Heavy, He's My Brother\", played over the end credits).\n\n# It Is Our Destiny \u2013 Bill Medley (4:30)\n# Preparations (4:58)\n# Afghanistan (2:35)\n# The Game (2:23)\n# Another Time (3:54)\n# He Ain't Heavy, He's My Brother \u2013 Bill Medley (4:30)\n# Aftermath (2:42)\n# Questions (3:34)\n# The Bridge - [[Giorgio Moroder]] featuring Joe Pizullo (3:59)\n# Final Battle (4:47)\n\nA more complete 75-minute version of the score was later released by [[Intrada Records|Intrada]].\n# Another Time (3:58)\n# Preparations (06:21)\n# The Money (0:52)\n# I'm Used To It (1:00)\n# Peshawar (1:12)\n# Afghanistan (2:38)\n# Questions (3:37)\n# Then I'll Die (3:34)\n# The Game (2:25)\n# Flaming Village (4:07)\n# The Aftermath (2:44)\n# Night Entry (3:58)\n# Under And Over (2:55)\n# Night Fight (6:50)\n# First Aid (2:46)\n# The Long Climb (3:25)\n# Going Down (1:52)\n# The Cave (3:31)\n# The Boot (1:53)\n# You Did It, John (1:08)\n# The Showdown (1:26)\n# Final Battle (4:50)\n# I'll Stay (9:00)\n\n==Release==\n\n===Box office===\n''Rambo III'' opened in the United States on May 25, 1988 at 2,562 theatres in its opening weekend (the four-day [[Memorial Day]] weekend), ranking #2 behind ''[[Crocodile Dundee II]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title= WEEKEND BOX OFFICE : Crocodile Swamps 'Rambo'; Hanks' 'Big' Hit |newspaper= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1988-06-14|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1988-06-14/entertainment/ca-4175_1_big-business|accessdate=2011-01-01|first=Nina|last=Easton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ad4cAAAAIBAJ&pg=3841,1104602 | title='Croc' devours 'Rambo' in first week in theaters | first=Ed | last=Blank | newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Press]] | accessdate=29 October 2010 }}</ref> Overall, the film grossed $53,715,611 domestically and then took $135,300,000 overseas, giving ''Rambo III'' a box office total of $189,015,611.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rambo3.htm|title=Rambo III (1988) - Box Office Mojo|website=Boxofficemojo.com|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref> The film underperformed at the box-office.<ref>{{cite news|title= Roger Rabbit' Hops to Box-Office Top; 'Coming to America' Hits 2nd|work= The Los Angeles Times|date=1989-01-05|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1989-01-05/entertainment/ca-271_1_box-office-information/2|accessdate=2010-10-29|first=Nina J.|last=Easton}}</ref>\n\nAudiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url=https://m.cinemascore.com |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nThe film scored a 37% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 34 reviews and with an average rating of 4.53/10. The sites critical consensus states that \"''Rambo III'' finds its justice-dispensing hero far from the thoughtful drama that marked the franchise's beginning -- and just as far from quality action thriller entertainment.\"<ref>{{Rotten tomatoes|id=rambo_iii}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the film a rating of 36 out of 100 based on 15 critic reviews, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Metacritic film|id=rambo-iii}}</ref>\n\nProminent critics [[Gene Siskel]] and [[Roger Ebert]] were split on ''Rambo III'', with Siskel awarding the film \"thumbs up\", and Ebert declaring \"thumbs down\" for those expecting more out of ''Rambo III''. Ebert did, however, give \"thumbs up\" to fans, saying the film was entertaining and that it \"delivers the goods\".\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' took a dim view of the film.<ref name=\"Maslin\"/>\n\nIn [[West Germany]], the [[Deutsche Film- und Medienbewertung (FBW)]], a government film rating office whose ratings influence financial support to filmmakers, earned criticism after it awarded a \"worthwhile\" rating (in German: ''wertvoll'') to ''Rambo III''.<ref>https://www.fbw-filmbewertung.com/film/rambo_3</ref>\n\nThe 1990 ''[[The Guinness Book of World Records]]'' deemed ''Rambo III'' the most violent film ever made, with 221 acts of violence, at least 70 explosions, and over 108 characters killed on-screen.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} However, the body count of the fourth film in the series, ''[[Rambo (2008 film)|Rambo]]'', surpassed that record, with 236 kills.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} The [[Mi-24|Mi-24 Hind-D]] helicopters seen in the film are in fact modified [[A\u00e9rospatiale]] [[A\u00e9rospatiale Puma|SA 330 Puma]] transport helicopters with fabricated bolt-on wings similar to the real Hind-Ds which were mainly used in the former [[Eastern Bloc]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} The other helicopter depicted is a slightly reshaped [[Aerospatiale Gazelle]].{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nSome have claimed that the dedication at the end of the film has been altered at various points in response to the [[September 11 attacks]]. Specifically it is claimed that the dedication was (at one point) \"to the brave Mujahideen fighters\" and then later changed to \"to the gallant people of Afghanistan\".{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} However, reviews of the film upon its release and later publications show that the film was always dedicated \"to the gallant people of Afghanistan\".<ref name=\"Maslin\">{{cite news|title= Reviews/Film; Stallone's 'Rambo III,' Globe-Trotting Cowboy For the 80's Audience |work= The New York Times|date=1988-05-25|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1988/05/25/movies/reviews-film-stallone-s-rambo-iii-globe-trotting-cowboy-for-the-80-s-audience.html|accessdate=2010-10-29|first=Janet|last=Maslin}}</ref><ref>''The Civil War in Popular Culture'' (1996). Washington D.C.: The Smithsonian Institution. {{ISBN|1560986875}}, p.152.</ref><ref>''Vietnam war films: over 600 feature, made-for-TV, pilot, and short movies, 1939-1992, from the United States, Vietnam, France, Belgium, Australia, Hong Kong, South Africa, Great Britain, and other countries'' (1994). Mcfarland & Co Inc Pub. {{ISBN|0899507816}}, p. 355.</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=8|[[Golden Raspberry Award|Razzie Award]]\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actor|Worst Actor]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Sylvester Stallone]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Sheldon Lettich]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]]\n|[[Richard Crenna]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]]\n|[[Mario Kassar]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Buzz Feitshans]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Andrew G. Vajna]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n|[[Peter MacDonald (film director)|Peter MacDonald]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Home media==\n''Rambo III'' was released on [[DVD]] on November 23, 2004, and a [[Blu-ray|Blu-Ray]] release followed on May 23, 2008. ''Rambo III'' was released on [[4K resolution|4K]] [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|UHD Blu-Ray]] on November 13, 2018.\n\n===Cut version===\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], the original theatrical trailer released worldwide by Columbia Pictures Industries, Inc. was rejected, but three versions appear on [[VHS]], DVD and Blu-ray and original theatrical release. The [[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]] rated the theatrical release 18 and later video releases rated 15. They also cut between two seconds and 65 seconds of the original film's runtime.<ref name=\"bbfc\">{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/rambo-iii-0 |title=BBFC Cinema Rating, 1988|website=Bbfc.co.uk|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref> Some later video releases almost tripled the cuts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/rambo-iii |title=BBFC Video Rating, 1989|website=Bbfc.co.uk|accessdate=17 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\n\n===Sequel===\n{{Main|Rambo (2008 film)}}\nA sequel titled ''Rambo'', was released in 2008.\n\n===Novelization===\n[[David Morrell]], author of ''[[First Blood (novel)|First Blood]]'', the novel the first ''Rambo'' film is based on, wrote a novelization called ''Rambo III''.\n\n===Comic books===\nA comic book adaptation of the film was published by [[Blackthorne Publishing]].<ref>{{gcdb issue|id=321002|title=Blackthorne Publishing: ''Rambo III''}}</ref><ref>{{comicbookdb|type=issue|id=109940|title=Blackthorne Publishing: ''Rambo III''}}</ref>  Blackthorne also published a 3D version of its ''Rambo III'' comic.\n\n===Video games===\nVarious companies released [[Rambo III (video game)|video games based on the film]], including [[Ocean Software]] and [[Taito]]. In 1990, Sega released its own game based on the film for the [[Master System]] and [[Sega Genesis|Genesis/Mega Drive]]. [[Sega]] later adapted some of the battle scenes in the film for the 2008 arcade game ''[[Rambo (2008 video game)|Rambo]]''. In 2014 was released ''[[Rambo: The Video Game]]'', based on the first three ''Rambo'' films.\n\n===Other references===\n* In the film ''[[The Texas Chainsaw Massacre 2]]'', the character of [[Chop Top]] jokes that the recording of one chainsaw murder sounds like \"the ''Rambo III'' soundtrack\", although at that time, there had only been two ''Rambo'' films.\n* In the film ''[[Twins (1988 film)|Twins]]'', [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]]'s character is seen looking at the poster of ''Rambo III'' featuring Stallone, where he compares his biceps to Stallone's, but waves it off with a smile while shaking his head and walks away.\n* In the film ''[[Hot Shots! Part Deux]]'', the protagonist Topper Harley ([[Charlie Sheen]]) is a parody of John Rambo and the plot of the film is the same as ''Rambo III'', which involves Harley rescuing his mentor, Col. Denton Walters (Richard Crenna, parodying his character from the ''Rambo'' franchise).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0095956}}\n* {{amg movie|40200}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=87653}}\n* {{AFI film|id=59082|title=Rambo III}}\n* {{mojo title|rambo3}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|rambo_iii}}\n* {{metacritic film|rambo-iii}}\n\n{{Rambo}}\n{{Sylvester Stallone}}\n{{Peter MacDonald}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rambo III}}\n[[Category:1988 films]]\n[[Category:1980s action films]]\n[[Category:1980s adventure films]]\n[[Category:1980s sequel films]]\n[[Category:1980s war films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action films]]\n[[Category:American anti-communist propaganda films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Carolco Pictures films]]\n[[Category:StudioCanal films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in Asia]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter MacDonald]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Jerry Goldsmith]]\n[[Category:Films set in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Israel]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Rambo]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Sylvester Stallone]]\n[[Category:Soviet\u2013Afghan War films]]\n[[Category:Films about United States Army Special Forces]]\n[[Category:1988 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Skywatcher68", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Distribution only.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rambo_III"}
{"title_page": "Ipoh", "text_new": "{{for|the federal constituency formerly represented in the Dewan Rakyat|Ipoh (federal constituency)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=October 2011}}\n{{Advert|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Ipoh\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of cities in Malaysia|City]] and [[List of capitals in Malaysia|state capital]]\n| official_name                   = City of Ipoh<br>{{nobold|''Bandaraya Ipoh''}}\n| translit_lang1                  = Other\n| image_skyline                   = Ipoh composite.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from top: Jalan Tun Sambanthan within the Old Town, [[Ipoh railway station|Railway Station]], City Hall, [[St. Michael's Institution]], Perak Tong Temple\n| image_flag                      = Flag of Ipoh, Perak.svg\n| flag_size                       = 115px\n| image_seal                      = Ipoh Emblem.svg\n| nickname                        = City of Millionaires, Bougainvillea City, Silver Valley\n| motto                           = Ipoh Bersih, Hijau dan Maju<br>\n({{lang-en|Ipoh Clean, Green and Progressive}})\n| image_map                       = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=shape|stroke-width=2|stroke-color=#000000|zoom=10|frame-lat=4.59722222222222|frame-long=101.075}}\n| map_caption                     = Location of Ipoh in Perak\n| pushpin_map                     = #Malaysia#Asia#Earth\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 275px\n| pushpin_map_caption             = {{Legend inline|#800000|outline=black}} '''Ipoh''' in {{Legend inline|#FEFEEF|outline=black}} '''[[Malaysia]]'''\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|04|35|50|N|101|04|30|E|region:MY|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|Malaysia}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States of Malaysia|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = \n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|Perak}}\n| established_title1              = Establishment\n| established_date1               = Around 1880\n| established_title2              = Granted States Capital status\n| established_date2               = 31 May 1937\n| established_title3              = Granted Municipality status\n| established_date3               = 31 May 1962\n| established_title4              = Granted City status\n| established_date4               = 27 May 1988\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Rumaizi Baharin\n| area_total_km2                  = 643\n| area_total_sq_mi                = <!-- Leave blank. Value will be auto-converted. -->\n| elevation_m                     = 21.95\n| elevation_ft                    = 72\n| population_total                = 657,892\n| population_as_of                = 2010\n| population_density_km2          = 1023\n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- Leave blank. Value will be auto-converted. -->\n| population_metro                = 737,861<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/BPD/ad_2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521201742/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/BPD/ad_2010.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Malaysia|Postcode]]\n| postal_code                     = 30xxx, 31xxx\n| area_code                       = 05\n| area_code_type                  = \n| iso_code                        = \n| website                         = {{URL|mbi.gov.my}}\n| unemployment_rate               = \n| translit_lang1_type1            = [[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]\n| translit_lang1_info1            = \u0625\u06a4\u0648\u0647\n| translit_lang1_type2            = [[Chinese language|Chinese]]\n| translit_lang1_info2            = \u6021\u4fdd\n| translit_lang1_type3            = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| translit_lang1_info3            = \u0b88\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcb\n| timezone                        = [[Malaysian Standard Time|MST]]\n| utc_offset                      = +8\n| timezone_DST                    = Not observed\n}}\n\n'''Ipoh''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|i\u02d0|p|o\u028a}}) is the capital city of the [[Malaysia]]n [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|state]] of [[Perak]]. Located by the [[Kinta River]], it is nearly {{Convert|180|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Kuala Lumpur]] and {{Convert|123|km|abbr=on}} southeast of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in neighbouring [[Penang]]. {{As of|2010}}, Ipoh contained a population of 657,892, making it the [[List of cities in Malaysia by population|third largest city in Malaysia by population]].<ref name=\"st1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/03ringkasan_kawasan_PBT_Jadual1.pdf|title=Population Distribution by Local Authority Areas and Mukims, 2010 (page 1 & 8)|publisher=Department of Statistics, Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205090002/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/03ringkasan_kawasan_PBT_Jadual1.pdf|archivedate=5 February 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOriginally a village, Ipoh began to grow rapidly in the 1880s after huge deposits of [[tin]] were discovered within its vicinity.<ref name=\":0\" /> By 1895, it was the second largest town within the [[Federated Malay States]], which also consisted of [[Selangor]], [[Negeri Sembilan]] and [[Pahang]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbi.gov.my/ms/pelawat/info-ipoh/page/0/1|title=Info Ipoh: Halaman 2 dari 2 {{!}} Portal Rasmi Majlis Bandaraya Ipoh (MBI)|website=mbi.gov.my|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> Ipoh was declared a city in 1988.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> However, following the depletion of its tin deposits and the collapse of tin prices in the 1970s, the city suffered decades of decline and neglect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/travel/malaysia/2012/01/09/ipoh/|title=Ipoh - Malaysia {{!}} The Star Online|last=Tam|first=Susan|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/02/22/the-city-that-tin-built/|title=The city that tin built|last=Tan|first=Peter|date=2015-02-21|website=BorneoPost Online {{!}} Borneo, Malaysia, Sarawak Daily News|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sleepy-ipoh-awakens|title=Sleepy Ipoh awakens|last=hermes|date=2016-03-22|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2017-08-21|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theedgeproperty.com.my/content/old-town-restored-rightful-place-history-ipoh|title=Old Town restored to rightful place in history of Ipoh|website=theedgeproperty.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, Ipoh's popularity as a tourist destination has been significantly boosted by efforts to conserve its [[British Empire|British]] colonial-era architecture.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The city is also well known for its [[Ipoh cuisine|cuisine]] and natural attractions, such as its limestone hills and caves within which Buddhist temples were built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipohecho.com.my/v4/article/2015/05/16/caves-of-the-kinta-valley|title=Ipoh Echo {{!}} Caves of the Kinta Valley|last=net|first=powered by iosc dot|website=IpohEcho.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> In addition, Ipoh has managed to maintain its reputation as one of the cleanest cities in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/08/14/ipoh-is-malaysias-cleanest-city/|title=Ipoh is Malaysia's cleanest city - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=thestar.com.my|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIpoh's location between [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] has made it a major land transportation hub within [[Peninsular Malaysia|West Malaysia]], with both the [[Keretapi Tanah Melayu|Malayan Railway]]'s [[KTM West Coast Railway Line|West Coast Line]] and the [[North\u2013South Expressway (Malaysia)|North-South Expressway]] cutting through the city. Aside from the land transportation links, Ipoh is also served by the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]].\n\nIpoh is known as the Hipster Capital of Malaysia by various tourism rating and official agencies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1160937/ipohs-hipster-town-image-reason-for-new-found-fame-mb-says|title=Malay Mail - Ipoh Hipster Town Image|last=|first=|date=|work=The Malay Mail|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://says.com/my/news/ipoh-listed-in-lonely-planet-best-in-asia-2016|title=SAYS|last=|first=|date=|work=SAYS DOT COM|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/03/03/from-sleepy-city-to-international-draw-new-york-times-hails-ipoh-as-hip-and-mustvisit-holiday-destin/|title=The Star Malaysia|last=|first=|date=|work=The Star Malaysia|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timetravelturtle.com/hipster-ipoh-malaysia/|title=Time Travel Turtle|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Travel Turtle|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIpoh grew out from the Malay village of Paloh along the banks of the Kinta River in the 1880s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://db.ipohworld.org/photo/pdf/3875_wzhem140612.pdf|title=The History of Ipoh|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Its geographic location in the rich tin-bearing valley of the [[Kinta River]] made it a natural centre of growth.\n\nThe Great Fire of Ipoh in 1892 destroyed over half the town, but also presented an opportunity to rebuild the town in a more orderly grid pattern. Ipoh was subsequently rebuilt in time for the second tin rush and grew rapidly as a result of the booming tin mining industry, particularly in the 1920s and 1930s.\n\nA local [[Hakka people|Hakka]] miner, millionaire Yau Tet Shin, started developing a large tract of the town in the early 1930s, today known as the 'New Town', from the eastern bank of the [[Kinta River]] to Greentown.<ref name=\"ipohworld762\">[http://www.ipohworld.org/blog/?p=762 Ipohworld\u2019s World \u00bb Yau Tet Shin\u2019s New Town Under Construction 1908]. Ipohworld.org. Retrieved 27 September 2013.</ref> In 1937, Ipoh was made the capital of Perak, replacing [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]].\n\nIpoh was invaded by the Japanese on 15 December 1941. In March 1942, the Japanese Civil Administration or Perak Shu Seicho was set up at the [[St. Michael's Institution]]. After the liberation of Malaya by British forces, Ipoh remained the capital of Perak to this day.<ref>Khoo Salma Nasution & Abdur-Razzaq Lubis, ''Kinta Valley: Pioneering Malaysia's Modern Development'', Ipoh: Perak Academy, 2005. pp. 273\u2013292</ref>\n\nThe decline of the tin mining industry during the latter half of the 20th century caused the growth of Ipoh to stagnate.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} With the closure of the tin mines, its urban population was forced to seek employment in other cities within Malaysia. In spite of this, Ipoh remains one of the largest cities in Malaysia in terms of population, with tourism now a main driver of the city's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.world-guides.com/asia/malaysia/perak/ipoh/ipoh_history.html|title=Ipoh History Facts and Timeline: Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia|website=world-guides.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIpoh gained Municipal status in 1962, and in 1988, was declared a city by the then [[Sultan of Perak]], [[Azlan Shah of Perak|Sultan Azlan Shah]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Geography ==\n{{Location map many|Malaysia Perak Ipoh|width=300|float=left\n|caption=Locations of Ipoh and its suburbs\n|lat1=4.597222|long1=101.075|label1_size=75 |label1='''Ipoh'''|position1=left\n|lat2=4.720754|long2=101.1212|label2_size=65 |label2=[[Chemor]]|position2=left|mark2=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat3=4.61831|long3=101.140884|label3_size=65 |label3=[[Tambun]]|position3=right|mark=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat4=4.638596|long4=101.0636|label4_size=65 |label4=[[Jelapang, Perak|Jelapang]]|position4=left|mark4=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat5=4.529513|long5=101.129836|label5_size=65 |label5=[[Simpang Pulai]]|position5=right|mark5=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat6=4.56836|long6=101.050314|label6_size=65 |label6=[[Menglembu]]|position6=left|mark6=Cyan pog.svg\n}}\n\n=== Topography ===\nIpoh is in the state of [[Perak]], which is in the northern part of [[Peninsular Malaysia]]. The city is in the middle of the [[Kinta Valley]], on the bank of the [[Kinta River]] and the confluence of smaller rivers, Sungai Pinji and Sungai Pari. The city is surrounded by limestone hills, which can be found around suburban areas to the northeast, east and southeast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiahotelreview.com/perak/destination/limestone-hill.shtml |title=Limestone Hills (Bukit Batu Kapur), Ipoh, PERAK \u2013 Malaysia Travel Review |publisher=Malaysiahotelreview.com |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Kledang mountain range stretches from the north to the west of the city. This range runs parallel to the [[Bintang Mountains|Bintang mountain range]] with the [[Perak River]] flowing on its left bank and the [[Kinta River]] to its right. This range is interrupted to the north of Ipoh by a tributary of the [[Perak River]] called the Pelus River, which is sourced from the [[Titiwangsa Mountains|Titiwangsa mountain range]], which runs to the east of Ipoh.<ref>{{cite book |last= Jacq-Hergoualc'h |first= Michel |author2=Victoria Hobson |title= The Malay Peninsula: Crossroads of the Maritime Silk Road (100 BC \u2013 1300 AD) |publisher= [[Brill Publishers|BRILL]] |date=September 2002 |isbn= 90-04-11973-6}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\nIpoh features a [[tropical rainforest climate]] more subject to the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] than the [[trade wind]]s and with very rare [[cyclone]]s so an equatorial climate. Temperatures are about the same throughout the year, showing little variation. The city's average temperature is {{Convert|28|C}}. Ipoh sees high precipitation throughout the year with an average of {{Convert|200|mm|abbr=on}} of rain each month and averaging {{Convert|2427.9|mm|abbr=on}} of rain per year. The wettest month is October where on average {{Convert|297.2|mm|abbr=on}} of rain is seen. Ipoh's driest month is January which has {{Convert|132.3|mm|abbr=on}} of rain fall on average.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Ipoh\n| metric first = y\n| single line  = y\n| Jan high C = 32.9\n| Feb high C = 33.7\n| Mar high C = 33.9\n| Apr high C = 33.7\n| May high C = 33.5\n| Jun high C = 33.3\n| Jul high C = 33.0\n| Aug high C = 33.0\n| Sep high C = 32.5\n| Oct high C = 32.4\n| Nov high C = 32.1\n| Dec high C = 32.1\n| year high C = 33.0\n| Jan low C = 22.6\n| Feb low C = 23.0\n| Mar low C = 23.4\n| Apr low C = 23.9\n| May low C = 24.0\n| Jun low C = 23.7\n| Jul low C = 23.2\n| Aug low C = 23.3\n| Sep low C = 23.2\n| Oct low C = 23.1\n| Nov low C = 23.1\n| Dec low C = 22.8\n| year low C = 23.3\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 132.3\n| Feb rain mm = 149.8\n| Mar rain mm = 169.9\n| Apr rain mm = 259.1\n| May rain mm = 210.9\n| Jun rain mm = 151.8\n| Jul rain mm = 156.6\n| Aug rain mm = 157.8\n| Sep rain mm = 216.0\n| Oct rain mm = 297.2\n| Nov rain mm = 275.4\n| Dec rain mm = 251.1\n| year rain mm = 2427.9\n| unit rain days = 1.0 mm\n| Jan rain days = 9\n| Feb rain days = 10\n| Mar rain days = 12\n| Apr rain days = 14\n| May rain days = 14\n| Jun rain days = 10\n| Jul rain days = 10\n| Aug rain days = 12\n| Sep rain days = 15\n| Oct rain days = 18\n| Nov rain days = 18\n| Dec rain days = 15\n| year rain days = 157\n| source 1 = [[World Meteorological Organisation]]<ref name= WMO>{{cite web\n| url = http://worldweather.wmo.int/020/c00077.htm\n| title = World Weather Information Service&nbsp;\u2013 Ipoh\n| publisher = World Meteorological Organisation\n| accessdate = 7 May 2014}}</ref>\n| date     = May 2014}}\n\n=== Limestone caves ===\n[[File:Gua Tempurung.jpg|thumb|The Gua Tempurung Limestone Caves|left]]\n\n[[File:SAM POH TONG LOKE 399.jpg|thumb|[[Sam Poh Tong]], one of the many temples in Ipoh]][[File:Gunung Lang.jpg|thumb|Lang Mountains in Ipoh|left]]\n\nLimestone outcrops rise on the outskirts of Ipoh. There are many caves in these outcrops; cave temples are built in some.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060706051626/http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 July 2006 |title=Home |publisher=Cavesofmalaysia.com |accessdate=10 December 2013 }}</ref> [[Sam Poh Tong]] is a notable one along with Kek Lok Tong (Chinese: \u6975\u6a02\u6d1e; Cavern of Utmost Happiness), which lies on the other side of the same outcrop. It is accessible through the Gunung Rapat housing area. It has a clean, quiet and cool environment. Other cave temples in Ipoh include Ling Sen Tong, Nan Tian Tong, Kwan Yin Tong and Perak Tong.\n\n[[Gua Tempurung]], near Gopeng south of Ipoh, is a show cave open to the public and popular among [[Caving|spelunkers]]. More than {{Convert|3|km|abbr=on}} long, it is one of the longest caves in Peninsular Malaysia. Part of it has been developed with electric lighting and walkways, and there are tours of different lengths and difficulty. A river passage runs about {{Convert|1.6|km|abbr=on}} through the hill. There are five very large chambers and some stalactites and stalagmites.\n\n== Famous for  \" Malay, Chinese, Indian\" Cuisine  ==\n{{Main|Ipoh cuisine}}\nIpoh has a vibrant food scene with a vast proliferation of hawker centres and restaurants. It is well known for dishes such as \"Sar Hor Fun\" ({{zh|c=\u6c99\u6cb3\u7c89}}) a complete one-dish rice noodle meal with prawn, meat, fish, vegetables and a savoury sauce. Other well known dishes from Ipoh include \"Hor Hee\", flat white rice noodles served with fish cakes and/or fish balls, \"Nga Choi Kai\" ({{zh|c=\u82bd\u83dc\u9e21}}), chicken with soy sauce and beansprouts topped with pepper,\"Kai Shi Hor Fun\" ({{zh|c=\u9e21\u4e1d\u6cb3\u7c89}}) rice noodles with Chicken, \"[[Hakka Mee]]\" ({{zh|c=\u5ba2\u5bb6\u9eb5}}), yellow rice noodles served with mince meat (pork) sauce, \"Tau Fu Fa\", soybean pudding, and Ipoh's famous pastry \"[[Heong Peng]]\" ({{zh|c=\u9999\u9905}}), literally translated to \"fragrant biscuit\". The city is well known in Malaysia for its \"[[Ipoh white coffee]]\" where the coffee beans are roasted with palm-oil margarine and the resulting coffee is served with condensed milk. Ipoh is also known for its fresh fruits such as Pomelo, Durian and Seedless Guava. Ipoh also the home of the famous Ipoh Nasi Kandar or Nasi Vanggey. The dish which is very famous among local citizen and most favorite afternoon dish. When it come's to malay cuisine the best part is their place set up like a village home serving amazing home food example: Nasi lemak with fried Country chicken spicy sambal \"Restoran nasi lemak ayam kampung\" use waze to travel this place. Did you know that IPOH ORIGINAL KACANG PUTIH which means IPOH INDIAN SNACKS is now world famous snack and Indians here now exporting their signature snacks to world wide. Little India is big street which is located in ipoh, famous for Indian cuisine like vegetarian : krishna bhagawan, anandha bhagawan  and for non vegetarian : Thirupathy vilas , old town chapthi . Furthermore, to taste the Authentic South Indian & Clay pot rice visit RESTORAN SRI NAVA JOHTHI 1996 which is located in BUNTONG,ipoh. Their dish normally less preventatives and more to a village method and Clay pot rice is their signature menu which mix with real herbs & spices can blow your mind.    \n\nIn recent years Ipoh has seen an increase in international restaurants, bars and gastropubs have become popular with locals and tourists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ipoh's bars, gastropubs and nightlife |url=http://travel-tourist-information-guide.com/malaysia-ipoh-bars-clubs-night-life-going-out-drinking-entertainment|website=Travel-Tourist-Information-Guide.com|accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Economy  ==\nThe early history Ipoh as a settlement was due to its mining industry although it was playing second fiddle to Gopeng, some 19&nbsp;km / 12 miles to the south.\nIpoh was once, one of the richest cities in Malaysia as well as South East Asia back in the days when tin was king. During the 1980s when tin prices collapsed, the economy of Ipoh was hit particularly hard. However, recently the city gain some momentum. By 2017, the city will open the first Movie Animation Theme Park (MAPS), which is the first ever in South East Asia. Tourism is booming in the city, and many shops in old town Ipoh is being transform into chic caf\u00e9. \nThe city of Ipoh also host some big multi national corporations. Kuala Lumpur Kepong (KLK) Berhad, a palm oil company, which is also among the top 15 biggest companies in Malaysia (By revenue) has its headquarters in Ipoh. \nBatu Kawan Berhad (Which is the biggest shareholder of KLK), an investment company also has its headquarters in Malaysia. \nHovid Berhad, a pharmaceutical company, which is also the first Malaysian companies to introduce generic drugs overseas also has its headquarters in Ipoh. Ipoh also is well known for its white coffee. Old Town Berhad, which is a food & beverage public listed company, specializing in white coffee has its headquarters in Ipoh. \nThere are a few other public listed companies in Ipoh such as Perak Transit Berhad, Tasek Cement Berhad, DKLS Industries Berhad, Wellcall Holding Berhad, Rubberex Berhad, Perak Corp, etc. Ipoh also host some foreign multi national companies Malaysian headquarters. Some of the foreign MNC's in Ipoh is, Finisar, Voith, ITL Asia pacific, Sagami Manufacturers, etc.\n\n== Cityscape ==\n[[File:Ipoh_58.jpg|thumb|Ipoh Skyline]]\n[[File:Ipoh, Perak.jpg|thumb|Jalan Laxamana]]\n\n=== The Old Town ===\nThe Old Town is west of the Kinta River. There is a vibrant commercial district with many historical 'shop-houses' centred around Leech Street ({{zh|c=\u70c8\u6cbb\u8857}}; now Jalan Bandar Timah). Other notable features include:\n* [[Ipoh railway station]] in neo-classical/[[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian Baroque]] style nicknamed the \"Taj Mahal of Ipoh\".\n* Ipoh Town Hall, an [[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian Baroque]] municipal building located across the road from the Railway Station.\n* Padang Ipoh or Ipoh Field is on Jalan S.P. Seenivasagam. The field is surrounded by historic buildings that feature classic colonial architecture, including the mock-Tudor style Ipoh Club, FMS Bar, HSBC Building and the [[St Michael's Institution]] secondary school.\n* The [[Anglo-Chinese School, Ipoh]], officially named SMK Methodist (ACS), is located along Lahat Road.\n* [[Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Anderson]] is the most well-known secondary school with more than 100 years of history, located beside the General Hospital of Ipoh. This school has been producing numerous of figures in the country.\n* [[St. Michael's Institution]], Ipoh, is a public secondary school in Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia. It is situated on Jalan S. P. Seenivasagam, formerly Clayton Road.\n* [[Han Chin Pet Soo (History Museum)|Han Chin Pet Soo]], the Hakka Tin Miner's Club, located on Jalan Bijeh Timah (formerly Treacher Street) has been restored and turned into Malaysia's First Hakka Tin Mining Museum.\n* Muzium Darul Ridzuan is a historical museum of Perak, in a pretty former tin-mining tycoon's mansion on Jalan Kuala Kangsar.\n*Concubine Lane or better known locally as Yi Lai Hong in Cantonese is a narrow and small lane located off Jalan Bandar Timah (Leech Street) in Old Town, Ipoh. It now has different restaurants, souvenir and gift shops and an entirely respectable hotel. To some locals, Concubine Lane is already becoming too busy.\n*Ipoh wall art murals drawn by talented street art artists clearly breathes in new life into Ipoh Old Town city. The murals do relive a sense of nostalgic moments related to Ipoh\u2019s heritage and culture. It is now a tourist attraction.\n[[File:Old Uncle with White Coffee.jpg|thumb|One of the 7 wall art murals drawn by Ernest Zacharevic in Ipoh old town.]]\n*[[Birch Memorial Clock Tower]] is a historical landmark which is located near the Ipoh State Mosque or commonly known as [[Sultan Idris Shah II Mosque]]. The clock tower was built to commemorate [[James W. W. Birch]], the first British Resident in Perak who was killed on 2 November 1875 at Pasir Salak.\n\n=== The New Town ===\n[[File:Tmn d.r.jpg|thumb|D.R. Seenivasagam Park, formerly Coronation Park]]\nThe so-called New Town, to the east of the Kinta River, was developed by [[Yau Tet Shin]] around 1908.<ref name=\"ipohworld762\" /> The New Town houses the [[Perak Medical University]] and [[Ipoh City Hall]] building, among others. There are numerous shops, shopping malls, and hotels.\n\nD. R. Seenivasagam Park (Coronation Park), located in the heart of Ipoh (New Town), is known for its scenery and recreational facilities.{{fact|date=March 2019}} It comprises recreational fields, an artificial lake filled with fish, a nursery for potted plants and a children's traffic playground.  The latest addition is the newly landscaped [[Japanese garden]] featuring a Japanese [[Koi|carp]] pond.\n\n== Sports ==\n\nFor golf, the courses are the Royal Perak Golf Club off Jalan Sultan Azlan Shah (Tiger Lane), the Meru Golf Club in [[Jelapang, Perak|Jelapang]], and Clearwater Sanctuary Golf Club en route to [[Batu Gajah]].\n\nOther sports venues include the Kilat Club in Pasir Pinji, Ipoh Field (Padang Ipoh) in the Old Town, the [[Polo]] Grounds, and the Iskandar Polo Club, in Ampang Baru.\n\nThe [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] is an annual international men's [[field hockey]] tournament held in Ipoh.\n\nIpoh has a fully equipped sports complex known as Kompleks Sukan MBI or ''MBI Sports Complex''.\n\nAmong the facilities located within the Complex is the Stadium Perak or [[Perak Stadium]]. [[Perak Stadium]] is the home of [[Perak FA|Perak The Bos Gaurus]] who playing in [[Malaysia Super League]].\n\n== Governance ==\n[[File:Ipoh City Council.jpg|thumb|[[Ipoh City Council]]]]\n\nThe [[Ipoh City Council]] governs the city. Datuk Zamri Man, appointed in August 2015, is the current mayor of Ipoh.<ref>{{Cite web|title = New mayor for Ipoh sworn in \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|url = http://www.thestar.com.my/Metro/Community/2015/08/10/New-mayor-for-Ipoh-sworn-in/|website = The Star|location=Malaysia|accessdate = 11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIpoh is divided into two parliamentary constituencies: ''Ipoh Barat'' (Ipoh West) and ''Ipoh Timur'' (Ipoh East). The parliamentary seat for ''Ipoh Timur'' is held by DAP Representative, Su Keong Siong, which was formerly held by [[Lim Kit Siang]] while the seat for ''Ipoh Barat'' is held by fellow DAP leader, [[M. Kulasegaran]].<ref>[http://temanpetunjuk.blogspot.com/2009/02/analisa-dewan-undangan-negeri-dun-perak.html]{{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nIpoh remains one of [[Malaysia]]'s largest cities. It is the third largest city in Malaysia. As of 2010, the municipal area of Ipoh has a population of 657,892.<ref name=\"census 2010\">{{cite web|title=Population Distribution by Local Authority Areas and Mukims, 2010|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/04Jadual_PBT_negeri/PBT_Perak.pdf|publisher=Department of Statistics Malaysia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227011347/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/04Jadual_PBT_negeri/PBT_Perak.pdf |archivedate=27 February 2012 }}</ref> It ranks as the seventh most [[List of urban areas in Malaysia by population|populous urban centre]] in Malaysia (2010).<ref name=\"census 2010\" />\n\nThe following is based on Department of Statistics Malaysia 2010 census.<ref name=\"census 2010\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=3| Ethnic groups in Ipoh, 2010\n|-\n! [[Ethnicity]] !! Population !! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] || 290,165 || 44.11%\n|-\n| [[Bumiputera_(Malaysia)|Bumiputera]] || 253,592 || 38.55%\n|-\n| [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] ||  92,587 || 14.07%\n|-\n| Others || 1,559 || 0.2%\n|-\n| Non-Malaysian || 19,989 || 3.04%\n|}\n\n=== Toponymy ===\nThe name Ipoh is derived from a local tree, ''Pohon Epu'' or now more commonly known as [[Upas Tree|''Pokok Ipoh'']]. The sap of this plant is poisonous and was used by [[Orang Asli]] ([[indigenous peoples]] in [[Malay language|Malay]]) to coat the tips of the darts of their blowpipes for hunting.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Sultan Azlan Shah Airport.JPG|thumb|[[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]]]]\n* Trunk roads: The old interstate [[Malaysia Federal Route 1|Route]] {{JKR|1}} connects Ipoh with other major towns and cities in peninsular Malaysia, for example to [[Alor Setar]], [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]] and [[Penang]] to the north and [[Tapah]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Seremban]] and even [[Johor Bahru]] in the south. Motorists from the east coast can use [[Malaysia Federal Route 4|highway]] {{JKR|4}} (from [[Gerik]]) in northern Perak or {{JKR|185}} (from [[Cameron Highlands]]).\n* Highway: The new [[North\u2013South Expressway (Malaysia)|North\u2013South Expressway]] {{MES-E|1}} is a faster and more efficient alternative to Route 1. However, certain towns like [[Kampar, Perak|Kampar]] can only be accessible via Route 1.\n* Train: [[Ipoh railway station|Ipoh's railway station]] is operated by [[Keretapi Tanah Melayu]] (KTM) and is in the Old Town (however, it does not have intra-city travel like in [[Kuala Lumpur]]). The railway only connects Ipoh with neighbouring towns and cities. The station is a stately building, referred to by locals as the 'Taj Mahal' of Ipoh. [[KTM Intercity]] began the Shuttle Train Service between [[Kuala Lumpur]] and Ipoh from 1 December 2008 while the modern [[Electric Train System]] (ETS) shuttle began from 12 August 2010 with average {{Convert|145|km/h|abbr=on}} speed, plying Ipoh-Seremban route, cut the travelling distance between Ipoh and [[Kuala Lumpur]] into 120&nbsp;minutes. There are 10 dedicated shuttle train services between these two cities daily which begins at 5&nbsp;am from both the stations. Travel time between the cities was expected to be reduced from three hours to two hours and fifteen minutes when the new set of EMU trains arrived in mid-2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cockatoo.com/malaysia/e-06pera/em-per27.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119155613/http://www.cockatoo.com/malaysia/e-06pera/em-per27.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 January 2013 |title=Malaysia / Perak / The Ipoh Railway Station |publisher=Cockatoo.com |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=10 December 2013 }}</ref>\n* Bus: The inter-city bus terminal is located at [[Amanjaya Integrated Bus Terminal]] in [[Bandar Meru Raya]], just north of the city.\n* Air:  the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]] is the only airport in Ipoh. It is near [[Gunung Rapat]]. Domestic flights and international ones are available. [[Scoot]] and [[AirAsia]] provides daily flights out of Ipoh to [[Singapore]] [[Changi Airport]] while [[Batik Air Malaysia]] provides daily flights to [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]].\nThere are also planned flights to Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand and China with talks of a new airport soon.\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|List of schools in Perak}}\n\nThis is a list of schools in Ipoh, Perak.\n*Sekolah Izzuddin Shah \n*[[Sekolah Tuanku Abdul Rahman]] \n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Tanjung Rambutan\n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Seri Puteri\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan(T)ST.Philomena Convent, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Dato Panglima'Kinta, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Yuk Choy, Ipoh\n*SMJK Yuk Choy, Ipoh\n*Tarcisian Convent School, Ipoh (TCS)\n*Anderson School, Ipoh\n*Anglo-Chinese School, Ipoh\n*[[St. Michael's Institution]], Ipoh\n*SMK Jalan Tasek, Ipoh \n*Methodist Girls Secondary School (MGS), Ipoh\n*Perak Girls Secondary School (PGS), Ipoh\n*[[SMK Main Convent]], Ipoh\n*Wesley Methodist School, Ipoh\n*Ipoh International School (Private)\n*Fairview International School, Ipoh\n*Perak Yuk Choy High School (Private) \n*Poi Lam High School (Private) \u6021\u4fdd\u57f9\u5357\u72ec\u7acb\u4e2d\u5b66 \n*Shen Jai High School, Ipoh \u6021\u4fdd\u6df1\u658b\u4e2d\u5b66\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Kerajaan, Sungai Pari, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Gunung Rapat, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Perak Sangeetha Sabha, Ipoh\n*SMK Rapat Setia, Ipoh\n*SMK Jalan Pasir Puteh, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Poi Lam, Ipoh\n*SMK Seri Keledang, Ipoh\n*SMK Menglembu, Ipoh\n*SMJK Poi Lam, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Sam Tet, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u4e09\u5fb7\u5c0f\u5b66}})\n*[[SMJK Sam Tet]], Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u4e09\u5fb7\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*SMK Dato Ahmad Said\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan Ave Maria Convent, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u5723\u6bcd\u739b\u5229\u4e9a\u5c0f\u5b66}})\n*SMJK Ave Maria Convent, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u5723\u6bcd\u739b\u5229\u4e9a\u56fd\u6c11\u578b\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Gunung Rapat, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Wan Hwa (1)\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Wan Hwa (2)\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan (ACS), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan (P) Methodist, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Haji Mahmud Chemor, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Kuala Pari, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Jalan Pegoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Jelapang\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Marian Convent,Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Raja Ekram, Ipoh\n*SMK Raja Perempuan, Ipoh (RPS) Royal Princess School \"Cluster School\"\n*SRK Raja Perempuan, Ipoh (RPS) \n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Seri Ampang, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan St. Michael's Institution (1), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan St. Michael's Institution (2), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Chung Shan\n\n== Theme Parks ==\nThere are several theme parks in Ipoh, including the Sunway Lost World of Tambun <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sunwaylostworldoftambun.com/|title=Lost World of Tambun Ipoh|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and Movies Animated Park Studios (MAPS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsperak.com/|title=Movies Animation Park, Ipoh Official Website|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207000455/http://www.mapsperak.com/|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\nFilm and Television:\n* [[Angie Cheong]]\n* [[Mimi Chu]]\n* [[Iqram Dinzly]]\n* [[Mamat Khalid]]\n* [[Peter Pek]]\n* [[Afdlin Shauki]]\n* [[Patrick Teoh]]\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]]\nMusic:\n* [[Guang Liang|Michael Wong]]\n* [[Jamal Abdillah]]\n* [[Shila Amzah]]\n* [[Ning Baizura]]\n* [[Francissca Peter]]\n* [[:ms:Sophia Liana|Sophia Liana]]\n* Sam Chin Neng of [[Fuying & Sam]]\nSports: (Badminton):\n* [[Koo Kien Keat]]\n* [[Choong Tan Fook]]\n* [[Lee Wan Wah]]\n* [[Cheah Soon Kit]]\n* [[Wong Pei Tty]]\n* [[Wong Mew Choo]]\nSports ([[Association football|Football]]):\n* [[Nazirul Naim]]\n* [[Chan Kok Heng]]\n* [[Muhamad Khalid Jamlus]]\nSports (Others):\n* [[Tony Underwood]] (Rugby)\n* [[Nur Suryani Mohd Taibi]] (Sports shooting)\n* [[Leong Mun Yee]] (Diving)\nBusiness:\n* [[David Ho Sue San]] of [[Hovid Berhad]] & Carotech Berhad,\n* [[Lee Loy Seng]] (founder of Kuala Lumpur Kepong Berhad),\n* Dr. [[Wong Jeh Shyan]] CEO of CommerceNet Singapore Limited,\n* [[Koon Yew Yin]] Founder of [[IJM Corporation Bhd]] and [[Gamuda Berhad]]\nPolitics:\n* [[Yeoh Ghim Seng]]\n* [[Yeoh Eng-kiong|Dr Yeoh Eng Kiong]]\n* [[S. J. V. Chelvanayakam]]\n* [[Ahmad Husni Hanadzlah]]\n* [[D. R. Seenivasagam]]\n* [[Lim Keng Yaik]]\n* [[Lee Lam Thye]]\n* [[Chang Lih Kang]]\n* [[Lee Chuan How]]\nHistorical:\n* [[Yusof bin Ishak]] (president of Singapore)\n* [[Leong Sin Nam]]\n* [[Wu Lien-teh]]\n* [[Foo Choo Choon]]\n* [[Leong Fee]]\n* [[Chung Thye Phin]]\n* [[Eu Tong Sen]]\n\nExperts and Academicians:\n* [[Lam Wei Haur]] (Professor Dr in Science)\n\nOther:\n\n* [[Chan Sek Keong]] (Chief Justice of Singapore)\n* [[Lat (cartoonist)|Lat]] (cartoonist)\n* [[Huen Su Yin]] (cake decorating)\n* [[Tang Siew Mun]] (academic)\n* [[Tang Tuck Kan]] (artist)\n\n== Film and television ==\nMovies filmed in Ipoh include:\n* 1992: ''[[Indochine (film)|Indochine]]''\n* 1999: ''[[Anna and the King]]''\n* 2004: ''Tun Tan Cheng Lock''{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n* 2005: ''[[Sepet]]''\n* 2005: ''[[Gubra]]''\n* 2006: ''After This Our Exile (''Chinese'' \u7236\u5b50)\n* 2006: ''Goodbye Boys''\n* 2006: ''[[Lust, Caution]]'' (Chinese: \u8272\uff0c\u6212)\n* 2015: ''[[Blackhat (film)|Blackhat]]''\n\n==Media==\n===[[List of newspapers in Malaysia|Nationwide/National daily newspaper]]===\n====English====\n*''[[Malay Mail]]''\n*''[[New Straits Times]]''\n*''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]''\n*''[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]]''\n====Malay====\n*''[[Berita Harian]]''\n*''[[Harian Metro]]''\n*''[[Sinar Harian]]''\n====Chinese====\n*''[[Nanyang Siang Pau]]'' \u2013 \u5357\u6d0b\u5546\u62a5\n*''[[Sin Chew Daily]]'' \u2013 \u661f\u6d32\u65e5\u62a5\n*''[[China Press]]'' \u2013 \u4e2d\u56fd\u62a5\n\n====Tamil====\n*''[[Makkal Osai]]'' \u2013 {{lang|ta|\u0bae\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b93\u0b9a\u0bc8}}\n*''[[Malaysia Nanban]]'' \u2013 {{lang|ta|\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe \u0ba8\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0baa\u0ba9\u0bcd}}\n===Ipoh [[terrestrial television|terrestrial channels]]===\nIpoh [[Free-to-air|free-to-air stations]] include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n![[Television station]]\n!Channel (via [[MYTV Broadcasting|myFreeview]])\n!Network\n!Broadcast area\n!Broadcast hour\n|-\n| [[TV1 (Malaysia)|TV1 HD]]\n| 101\n| rowspan=2| [[Radio Televisyen Malaysia|RTM]]\n| rowspan=14| National\n| rowspan=5| [[24/7]]\n|-\n| [[TV2 (Malaysia)|TV2 HD]